<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Foreign Trade Dips in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Canada's foreign trade volume
dipped about 1 percent in June to 33.7 billion U.S. dollars,
Statistics Canada reported today.
</P>
<P>
Canada's exports dropped by 1.1 percent in June to 17.5 billion
dollars, after a 0.8 percent gain in May.
</P>
<P>
Most of the drop is the result of a decline in exports of
automotive products and machinery, which fell by 5.8 percent and
2.1 percent respectively, the federal statistics agency said.
</P>
<P>
Only the export of energy products posted a gain, climbing 3.0
percent, as the export of crude petroleum, natural gas and
electricity all went up.
</P>
<P>
The country's imports declined by 1 percent to 16.2 billion
dollars, following a hike in April and little change in May.
</P>
<P>
Most of the decline resulted from lower imports of machinery
and equipment, which dropped by 3.8 percent, and industrial goods,
which sank by 3.0 percent. Canada's import of these products had
been climbing steadily over the last year.
</P>
<P>
In June, Canada reaped a trade surplus of 1.3 billion dollars,
the agency said.
</P>
<P>
For the first half of this year, the country's trade surplus
was at 9.7 billion dollars, compared with a record 15.5 billion
dollars for the same period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
"Most of the decline can be attributed to strong import growth
in business investment related goods and low growth in automotive
and energy products," the agency said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
