<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Consumer Confidence at 10-Year High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 20 (Xinhua) -- UK's consumer confidence has
risen to its highest level in more than a decade, threatening a
rerun of the late-1980s boom, according to the European
Commission's monthly consumer survey.
</P>
<P>
The consumer confidence has risen steadily since the Labor came
to power in May and now equals the highest-ever level recorded in
June 1987, this month's survey suggests. August is normally a time
of relatively depressed economic activity.
</P>
<P>
The confidence has received a further boost from large windfall
payouts over the course of the last month or two. The latest
estimates suggest that consumers will receive windfall payouts
totaling about 56 billion US dollars by year-end.
</P>
<P>
Economists in the City expect that consumers' expenditure will
grow by about 4.5 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
Consumers are showing uncanny parallels with their behaviors
during the "Lawson boom", said Ben Sanderson, an economist at
Nottingham Trent University.
</P>
<P>
The proportion of consumers believing now is a good time to
make big purchases rose to 40 percent in August, up a third over
the last three months. Only half as many think big purchases
should be postponed.
</P>
<P>
However, with base rates having risen by 1 percent since the
election, observers here believe that it will prevent a full-scale
overheating of overall consumer activity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
