<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Hails Progress in Georgia-Abkhazia Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 20 (Xinhua) -- France today hailed the
"encouraging" progress being made by Georgia and Abkhazians in
their peace talks, in which both sides have agreed not to resort
to force in solving their dispute over the status of Abkhazia.
</P>
<P>
"If it appears that a number of questions, in particular that
of the status of Abkhazia, remains in suspense, the two parties
are engaged not to resort to force in whatever forms," said French
Foreign Ministry spokesman Yves Doutriaux.
</P>
<P>
He praised the "political courage" shown by Georgian President
Edouard Shevardnadze in engaging in the dialogue with the
Abkhazians to end the five-year-old war in which thousands were
killed and 250,000 made homeless.
</P>
<P>
Shevardnadze and Abkhazian leader Vladislav Ardzinba signed
last Thursday a declaration of peace in Tbilisi, capital of
Georgia, under the mediation of Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeni
Primakov.
</P>
<P>
Shevardnadze said that the declaration "unblocks" the way
toward real reconciliation between Georgians and Abkhazians and
for the future return of Georgian refugees to Abkhazia.
</P>
<P>
However, it failed to mention either the status of Abkhazia or
the destiny of an estimated 270,000 Georgian refugees who have
fled Abkhazia.
</P>
<P>
Abkhazia declared independence in August 1990 after the
breaking out of ethnic violence between Georgians and Abkhazians.
</P>
<P>
Georgia has rejected the claim for independence by Abkhazians
and only agrees to grant the territory enlarged autonomy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
