<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trade Deficit Falls Sharply in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. trade deficit
decreased sharply to 8.16 billion U.S. dollars in June, the lowest
level in three months, according to an official report from the
Department of Commerce today.
</P>
<P>
The trade deficit came down as the U.S. exports climbed to an
all-time high and imports dropped for the first time in eight
months.
</P>
<P>
The report noted that the overall deficit shrank by 14.5
percent to 8.16 billion. It was the lowest figure since March and
compared to a trade gap of 9.54 billion dollars in May.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. deficit with Mexico, which had climbed to record
levels, narrowed 29 percent to 1.2 billion dollars in June as
American exports hit an all-time high.
</P>
<P>
According to the U.S. department's report, the deficit with
China was up 14.5 percent to 4.3 billion dollars, reflecting big
increases in imports of Chinese clothing, shoes and toys.
</P>
<P>
The trade gap with Japan rose by 11.6 percent to 4.1 billion
dollars in June as imports of Japanese office machines and cars
rose sharply.
</P>
<P>
Overall, U.S. exports of goods and services edged up 0.9
percent to a record high of 78.4 billion dollars. Imports, which
had set seven straight monthly records, dipped a slight 0.7
percent to 86.6 billion dollars. It was the first decline since
last October.
</P>
<P>
The country's foreign oil imports declined by 4.5 percent in
June to 5.8 billion dollars. The volume of oil imports was down
slightly while the average price per barrel of crude oil was up
slightly to 17.07 dollars as against 17 dollars in May.
</P>
<P>
Despite of the better-than-expected performance in June, the
U.S. trade deficit for the first half of this year is running at
an annual rate of 111.1 billion dollars, placing the country on
track for its worst trade performance since 1988. 
</P>
</TEXT>
