<HEADLINE> Africa Needs Funds to Fight Locusts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The capacity by the
International Red-Locust Control Organization for Central and
Southern Africa (IRLCO-CSA) to fight the looming locust plague
has been impaired by low stocks of pesticides.
</P>
<P>
Zambia News Agency today quoted IRLCO-CSA Scientific Official
John Bahana as saying in northern Zambia on Tuesday that there is
a real danger of an invasion of locusts in the region and the
member countries of the organization should pay their
contributions.
</P>
<P>
Bahana said the organization is prepared to fight the invasion
but needs funds to procure pesticides.
</P>
<P>
While aircraft for the task are available, stocks of
pesticides for daily operations can only last one month, he said.
</P>
<P>
The major problem faced by the organization is failure by the
member countries to pay their contributions, he said.
</P>
<P>
Bahana said operations have been carried out in Malawi and
Botswana recently and a team is currently in Tanzania carrying
out a similar task after winds from an outbreak area blew the
pests to Burundi.
</P>
<P>
The swarms could have easily entered Zambia if it blew the
locusts southwards, he said.
</P>
<P>
The member countries of the organization are Tanzania, Kenya,
Uganda, Zambia, Malawi, Mozambique, Swaziland, Zimbabwe and
Botswana. 
</P>
</TEXT>
