<HEADLINE> More Contraceptives to be Provided in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The government is making
efforts to operate clinics at villages and provide contraceptives
as more as possible to check the growing population, Nepali Health
Minister Radha Krishna Mainali said today.
</P>
<P>
The target has been set to reduce the fertility rate to four
percent from 4.6 percent by 2000 in accordance with the national
health policy, Mainali said when answering queries at the Upper
House.
</P>
<P>
The population of Nepal, which stands at 21 million, is now
growing at an alarming rate of 2.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
He said those using contraceptives now number 295,000 and 35
percent of the newly married couples are using them, reported the
official RSS news agency.
</P>
<P>
Though the availability of doctors is only 60 percent in the
country, the policy to send doctors to posts outside the Kathmandu
Valley will be pursued seriously, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Due to lack of doctors and facilities, dozens of patients have
died of gastroenteritis, cholera, diarrhea, measles, rabies and
snake bites throughout the country, especially in the countryside.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
