<DOCNO> XIE19970821.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Banks Lose $12m to Swindler </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 20 (Xinhua) -- A man masquerading as a
reputable businessman owning more than 20 firms has fled Kenya
after defrauding seven Kenyan commercial banks of over 800
million Shillings (some 12 million U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Asian-origin man, identified as Satish Naker, stole the
money between January and July by kiting checks between the banks
and by obtaining loans through his companies that he has left
unpaid, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Naker is said to own Naker Printers and Packaging of Thika,
among other companies.
</P>
<P>
He used his charm to convince the banks to pay him large sums
in advance against the strength of checks from other banks.
</P>
<P>
"The affected banks relaxed their conditions because they
trusted him... and he appeared wealthy," said a banking source.
</P>
<P>
However, another banking source said Naker was not working
alone and there might be some insiders who helped in the
transaction.
</P>
<P>
Three senior officials from Standard Chartered Bank, the
hardest hit, had been arrested by Tuesday when a series of theft
charges were filed against Naker in a Nairobi court.
</P>
<P>
But as soon as the massive fraud came to light, Naker went
underground and is likely to be on the run in an Asian country,
according to a source from the Central Bank of Kenya (CBK).
</P>
<P>
So far the investigation is continuing and the Interpol is
expected to be requested for assistance to have Naker tracked
down and extradited back to Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Naker's victims also include Barclays Bank, First National
Finance Bank, Guardian Bank, Euro Bank, Guilders International
Bank and the Trust Bank, all based in Nairobi or the nearby Thika
town.
</P>
<P>
Most of the banks reportedly have a serious liquidity crisis,
prompting CBK's intervention.
</P>
<P>
The CBK source said his bank is holding discussions with the
affected banks so as to ensure that adequate financial measures
are being made to cover their losses and protect depositors.
</P>
<P>
Kiting is the act of issuing checks against companies said to
be owned by one person or group when they know they have no
money. They then wait for the clearance of one check and bring
more, posing the impression of having a lot of money.
</P>
<P>
Naker's case came only several months after a business tycoon
identified only as Shah defrauded more than 14 banks and several
major corporations of two billion Shillings (some 36 million
Dollars then) before fleeing this east African country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
