<HEADLINE> "Distance Education" Popular in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 20 (Xinhua) -- "Distance education", a new way
to offer people higher education outside universities, are
getting very popular in Zimbabwe, an official said today.
</P>
<P>
Program coordinator Stanley Tichaponda said they have received
more than 6,000 applicants since July, and that most of the
applicants show a great interest in the recently introduced
degrees in English, communication and agriculture, and a diploma
in classroom text and discourse.
</P>
<P>
"The response has been overwhelming and we do not even know
how we are going to respond to the applicants," he said.
</P>
<P>
The concept of distance learning was introduced in 1993 after
the government realized that there was great demand for higher
education which the country's limited number of universities
could not satisfy.
</P>
<P>
The applicants, Tichaponda said, were from various sectors
including journalists, teachers and customs and excise officials
and school leavers.
</P>
<P>
Although it was initially agreed that all applicants would be
accommodated, he said, the overwhelming response could result in
the college being forced to limit its intake.
</P>
<P>
The courses of distance education will start next Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
