<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bloody Violence Continues Shaking Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Week-long bloody violence
around Mombasa, Kenya's second-largest city and key Indian Ocean
port, has so far claimed 39 lives and dozens of injured. This has
deeply shaken the country facing a general election this year.
</P>
<P>
Up to date, no one knows actually the identity of the armed
killers, whose number can only be vaguely estimated to range from
200 to 500, needless to say their motives.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan police have arrested nearly 200 people over the killing
on the coast, including more than 30 ex-servicemen and an alleged
key activist with the ruling Kenya African National Union (KANU)
party, a local report reaching here said today.
</P>
<P>
The self-styled Chairman of Coast Youth for KANU, Omar
Masumbuko, was reportedly arrested at Mombasa this morning and
he now is being questioned by the police.
</P>
<P>
KANU Secretary-General J. Kamotho denied strongly Tuesday any
involvement of KANU in the orgy of bloodshed, while calling on
the law enforcement agencies to "do everything possible to
restore peace and transquility in the area."
</P>
<P>
Despite mounting efforts by Kenyan police and paramilitary
troops to restore peace, the terror has even spread to the
tourist resort Malindi, 120 kilometers north of Mombasa, where
two people were killed and 375 curio stalls burned Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In Mombasa, four people died in bloodshed early Tuesday and
two churches were burnt to ashes on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
No tourists have been hurt but foreigners have been told by
their governments to avoid trouble spots and the United States
has warned its citizens against going to the Kenyan coast.
</P>
<P>
A considerable number of foreign tourists have reportedly
canceled their booking in hotels in Mombasa and Malindi due to
the violence, said local press reports.
</P>
<P>
Seven police officers and eight civilians including five
attackers were killed at Likoni, south of Mombasa last Wednesday,
sparking a new wave of disturbance in Kenya which has experienced
several rounds of unrest since May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
