<DOCNO> XIE19970821.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Intra-COMESA Trade Shoots Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Intra-Common Market for East and
Southern Africa (COMESA) trade had grown from 9.59 billion
Zimbabwe Dollars in 1985 to 27.6 billion in 1994, acting
Secretary General Erastus Mwencha said today.
</P>
<P>
Currently one U.S. Dollar equals to 11.5 Zimbabwe Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference Mwencha said this had been a
result of a tariff reduction coupled with the removal of
non-tariff barriers.
</P>
<P>
"This translates into an average annual trade growth rate of
11.1 percent, compared with an average annual trade growth of 6.5
percent between COMESA and non-COMESA countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
For Zimbabwe, he said, intra-COMESA trade currently stood at
4.4 Billion Zimbabwe Dollars while Zimbabwean exports accounted
for 32 percent of total intra-COMESA imports.
</P>
<P>
COMESA was poised to establish a Free Trade Area (FTA) by the
year 2000 given the fact that Zimbabwe, Comoros, Sudan and Uganda
had reduced their tariff rates by 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
Eritrea, Kenya, Malawi and Mauritius had reduced their tariff
rates by 70 percent, and would be effecting the 80 percent
reduction rate in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Burundi, Rwanda and Zambia had reduced their tariff rates by
60 percent, while Lesotho, Namibia and Swaziland had not reduced
tariffs because they still enjoyed derogation and, subject to
agreement, expected to implement the COMESA tariffs after the
expiry of the derogation.
</P>
<P>
The year 2000 would see the COMESA single market, with a
combined gross domestic product of 1.38 trillion Zimbabwe Dollars
and a total population of 320 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970821.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Trader Does Well out of Arms Export </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Rosvooruzheniye, Russia's state
arms trading company, may earn more than 10 billion U.S. dollars
by the end of the year, the company's director-general Alexander
Kotelkin said at a press conference in the town of Zhukovsky
outside Moscow, where the MAKS-97 air show is being held.
</P>
<P>
The Interfax quoted Kotelkin as saying that the package of
orders amounted to 7 billion U.S. dollars as of August 1, while
his company had already received 3,000 orders.
</P>
<P>
He said the company is planning to sign contracts worth 3-3.5
billion U.S. dollars before the end of the year. Contracts on
ships and naval equipment supplies worth 2.8 billion U.S. dollars
are expected to be signed within the next two months, he added.
</P>
<P>
According to the high-ranking official, China is the second
largest buyer, after India, of Russia's aircraft. It has bought 50
Su-27SK fighters from Russia since 1992.
</P>
<P>
China has also paid Russia 1.5 billion U.S. dollars to buy a
license to manufacture 200 SU-27SK fighters within 15 years without
the right to re-export them, Kotelkin said.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that China is now considering purchasing 55 more
SU-27SK fighters from Russia.
</P>
<P>
Kotelkin also called a contract with Malaysia to sell it 18
MiG-29 planes worth 560 million U.S. dollars as a "breakthrough of
Russian weapons and military equipment to Southeast Asia."
</P>
<P>
Six SU-27 fighters worth 180 million U.S. dollars have been
sold to Vietnam which plans to buy 24 more planes to a total amount
of about 800 million U.S. dollars, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Kotelkin stressed that the Philippines and Thailand have also
shown keen interest in buying Russian MiG-29s.
</P>
<P>
It was said Rosvooruzheniye is trying to establish contacts
with Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Indonesian government has announced its decision
to buy 12 SU-30K fighters and eight MI-17-1B helicopters.
</P>
<P>
According to a report, in 1994-1996, Russia sold Colombia and
Peru 10 MI-17 helicopters and eight MI-24 helicopters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
