<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Aid Workers Killed in S. Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Mogadishu, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Two Somali aid workers were
shot dead in the Southern port of Kismayu, 500 km south of
Mogadishu today.
</P>
<P>
According to reports obtained through the VHF radios in the
town, the Somali aid workers were serving the International Aid
Agency, World Concern, which is one of the few agencies opening
in the town.
</P>
<P>
The sources added that one of the victims is Saa'id Omar who
has been a nurse in the outdoor clinic of the agency, while the
other is his nephew, Abdi Shukri, serving as a security man.
</P>
<P>
Gunmen have attacked the two while they were doing their
routine business.
</P>
<P>
The reason for the attack is reported to be a retaliatory
action by the Majerten clansmen following the killing of three of
their men in a car looting attempt by Marehan militiamen outside
Kismayu last week.
</P>
<P>
Both victims belong to the Marehan clan whose militiamen were
ousted from the town during the height of the fighting in and
around it little more than two months ago.
</P>
<P>
However, Omar and his nephew were among few individuals who
remained in Kismayu despite the dislodging of their clansmen to
continue their jobs for World Concern.
</P>
<P>
This killing today might jeopardize a low-level reconciliatory
meeting between the elders of the two clans in the region.
</P>
<P>
It may also threaten the operations of the international
agencies.
</P>
<P>
The town has been quiet since late June even though there has
been no official cease-fire and agreements between the two clans
who bitterly misunderstood over the control of the key
installations of the town, the air and seaport.
</P>
<P>
Kismayu is controlled by the son-in-law of Somalia's late
dictator, General Mohamed Said Hirsi Morgan who only two weeks
ago returned.
</P>
<P>
Morgan who himself belongs to the Majertem clan has been
abroad during the fighting with the Marehan clansmen who are now
allied with South Mogadishu faction leader, Hussein Mohamed
Aidid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
