<DOCNO> XIE19970821.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-20 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Blames Turkish Cypriot Side for Talks' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Russia has blamed the Turkish
Cypriot side for the failure of the second round of direct talks
between the two communities on the island, Cyprus News Agency
(CNA) reported today.
</P>
<P>
The responsibility for the failure in the international peace
efforts "weighs on the leadership of the Turkish Cypriot
community," CNA quoted a spokesman of the Russian Foreign Ministry
as saying in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman noted that the Turkish Cypriot side should also
be blamed for blocking a successful conclusion to the second round
of direct talks which took place last week in Glion, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
He described the stance of the Turkish Cypriot community's
leadership in Glion as "clearly obstructionist."
</P>
<P>
He said that the threats made by the Turkish side at the talks
to partially integrate the Turkish-occupied northern Cyprus to
Turkey if the European Union starts accession negotiations with
Cyprus early next year are "undoubtedly contrary to the U.N.'s and
the Security Council's stated positions."
</P>
<P>
The Russian Foreign Ministry official pointed out that these
kinds of threats are contrary to the 1977-1979 High Level
agreements reached between the two communities.
</P>
<P>
They are also contrary to the U.N. General Assembly resolutions
which repeatedly call on all nations to respect the island's
sovereignty, independence and territorial integrity, he added.
</P>
<P>
But the spokesman welcomed the readiness expressed by both
Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash to continue their meeting in Nicosia to discuss
humanitarian issues.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders had two meetings last month in Nicosia,
following the first round of direct talks held in Troutbeck,
near New York on July 9-12.
</P>
<P>
The meetings ended with an agreement on humanitarian issues
including solving the long-standing issue of missing persons
during the event of Turkish military intervention in 1974.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since the 1974 Turkish military
intervention in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with
Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
