<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Great Wall Helps Cement Friendship between Youths of China, Japan (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Developing the Sino-Japanese
friendly relationship of the 21st century is just like walking
uphill on the Great Wall, Japanese trade union leader Yasuo
Enomoto said here today.
</P>
<P>
"We are climbing to a greater height with each step and seeing
young people following in our footsteps," he said.
</P>
<P>
Enomoto, vice-president of the All-Japan Prefectural and
Municipal Workers Union, is one of the 300-plus Japanese trade
union members among 600 guests attending a celebration to mark the
25th anniversary of the normalization of relations between China
and Japan.
</P>
<P>
The event was held today at the Badaling section of the Great
Wall north of Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Three decades ago, at the age of 26, Enomoto visited the Great
Wall as a member of a Japanese youth delegation to China.
</P>
<P>
"We had to overcome enormous obstacles to come to China,
because Japan and China had not normalized relations with each
other at that time," he recalled.
</P>
<P>
"Now, numerous Japanese young people of the age I was at the
time scale the Great Wall. The current friendly relationship
between the two countries was painstakingly won. So it should be
treasured," he said.
</P>
<P>
For many Japanese and Chinese people, the Great Wall is a
special place where they can go to reflect on the past.
</P>
<P>
The Great Wall witnessed the first battles of the War of
Resistance against Japanese Aggression in the 1930s. Four decades
later, it greeted the footsteps of Kakuei Tanaka, the late
Japanese Prime Minister who worked with the later Chinese leader
Mao Zedong to realize the normalization of bilateral relations in
1972. In the past 25 years, many noted personalities from Japan,
such as Emperor Akihito, visited the Great Wall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970821.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Great Wall Helps Cement Friendship between Youths of China, Japan (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Twenty-five-year-old Kyoko Katashiba said today her first trip
to China has left her a deep impression.
</P>
<P>
"The Great Wall is so great. It is an embodiment of the Chinese
culture. It is like a tie of friendship that closely joins the
youths of the two countries," she said.
</P>
<P>
Touching the weathered wall, high school teacher Hiromi
Yamashita said he will tell his students the truth about what
happened between Japan and China in the past in order to make them
always remember the history.
</P>
<P>
"For many young Japanese, knowing about the Great Wall is the
starting point of knowing China," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We shouldn't send our children to the battlegrounds any more,"
said Yishii Ryoichi, president of the Teachers Trade Union of
Hyogo-ken of Japan.
</P>
<P>
This was his 16th visit to the Great Wall. When he was a
primary school student at the end of the war, his school building
was bombed. Now in his 60s, he believes such tragedy should never
happen again.
</P>
<P>
Ryoichi has led the trade union to compile a textbook for
Japanese school children to gain an accurate understanding of
Japan's aggression against China in history.
</P>
<P>
Though 71-year-old Japanese professor Akio Sugiyama was walking
some distance behind the young climbers, he said he still hopes
"the young people will pass me. They are younger and they should
do better than us."
</P>
<P>
Seeing the young people racing to the top of a hill, Daisaku
Kohchiyama, vice-president of the Japanese Trade Union
Confederation, said the younger generation should take the
responsibility to further nurture the good-neighborly relationship
between Japan and China, which was forged by the older generations.
</P>
<P>
To bring up young people to be able to carry on the Japan-China
friendship is at the top of the agenda of trade unions of both
sides, Kohchiyama said. Large-scale exchanges between young people
will strongly push forward bilateral ties with an eye to the 21st
century.
</P>
</TEXT>
