<DOCNO> XIE19970821.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-20 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Parliament Approves President's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Parliament dominated by
the conservatives approved today all of the 22-ministers proposed
by liberal President Mohammad Khatami.
</P>
<P>
The vote in favor of Khatami's cabinet showed the power and
influence that the 54-year-old president has gained from the 62
million populated nation since his inauguration on August 4.
</P>
<P>
Kamal Kharrazi became the foreign minister, Ali Shamkhani the
defense minister, and Hossein Namazi the economic minister.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet has an average age o 46.7 and it is well-educated
six PhDs, three of them U.S.-educated.
</P>
<P>
Earlier parliamentary sources had predicted that five of
Khatami's ministers, namely ministers of education, interior,
culture, housing and urban development would not receive the
required vote of confidence.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said that the vote of confidence signaled the
beginning of a honeymoon between the leftist-dominated cabinet and
the rightist-dominated Parliament known as Islamic Consultative
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Culture and Islamic Guidance Ataollah Mohajerani,
a liberal who has vowed to transform the ministry, received the
lowest votes of confidence today as only 144 out of 266 members
of parliament voted in his favor.
</P>
<P>
In order to secure vote of confidence for all his proposed
ministers, Khatami made two speeches Tuesday morning and this
afternoon, defending his proposed cabinet members.
</P>
<P>
He said that his nominees were "effective administrators" and
none of them went against the views of Khamenei, Iran's supreme
leader.
</P>
<P>
Khatami reiterated his pledge to the nation: "I will keep my
election promises: Respect for the law and the rule of the law,
freedom of expression, a public voice in national affairs, and
national independence."
</P>
<P>
In a move warmly welcomed by the public this week, every
proposed minister outlined in detail the programs he will
implement in office, and biographies were released to newspapers
all over Iran. 
</P>
</TEXT>
