<HEADLINE> France Calls on Warring Sides of Congo Republic to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 20 (Xinhua) -- France today called on the two
warring sides of the Congo Republic to stop fighting, as combat
intensified between the troops loyal to President Pascal Lissouba
and the Cobra militiamen supporting former president General Denis
Sassou Nguesso.
</P>
<P>
"There is an absolute emergency for a stop of the combat,"
said French Foreign Ministry spokesman Yves Doutriaux.
</P>
<P>
Reports from Brazzaville said that forces supporting Lissouba
have carried a major victory by capturing several districts of in
the central and northern parts of the capital from the militiamen
supporting Sassou Nguesso early this week.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also called on the two warring sides to "re-take
their discussions to lead to as quickly as possible an accord
allowing the deployment of a peace-keeping force by the United
Nations."
</P>
<P>
The United Nations High Commission for Refugees has confirmed
that the forces of Lissouba have also captured Ouesso, the largest
city in the northern part of Congo Republic.
</P>
<P>
France, which has scrapped its traditional interventionist
policy toward Africa, is keeping a distance from the war in Congo
Republic, although it has key strategic interests in the oil
resources of the country.
</P>
<P>
The mediation offered by Gabonese President Omar Bongo and
United Nations envoy Mohamed Sahnoun has so far failed to bring
about any results, while President Laurent-Desire Kabila of the
Democratic Republic of Congo has offered to intervene in the
conflict. 
</P>
</TEXT>
