<HEADLINE> German Finance Minister Denies to Quit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 20 (Xinhua) -- German Finance Minister Theo Waigel
has rejected the speculations that he may give up his post after
the general elections in September next year, his aides said
today.
</P>
<P>
Waigel had never said how long he would remain as finance
minister, said a spokeswoman of the Finance Ministry on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Waigel is fulfilling his mandate. What will happen afterwards
depends on what the voters decide," the spokeswoman added.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of Waigel's party, the Christian Social Union
(CSU), today also said that Waigel had not set the election day as
deadline for his minister term. "It does not make sense to
speculate about it," he added.
</P>
<P>
The speculations about Waigel's quit was sparked by himself
during an interview with the German Bayerische Rundfunk radio on
Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
"Nine or ten years as finance minister are enough....This is
more than could have been expected from me. I've done my duty and
I'm still doing it. But then it will be enough," Waigel was quoted
as saying in the interview.
</P>
<P>
Waigel, 58, has been finance minister in Chancellor Helmut
Kohl's center-right government since April 1989. He has come under
sharp criticism recently for his hardline management of the
government budget and the proposed tax reform as Germany is
struggling to reduce record high unemployment and to make the
grade to join the planned single European currency, the Euro.
</P>
<P>
Waigel also triggered off controversies recently for his
suggestion of a cabinet reshuffle before the general election next
year.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Waigel's unexpected remarks at Tuesday's
interview, Rudolf Scharping, parliamentary leader of the main
opposition Social Democratic Party (SPD), said that it was a
"recognition of defeat" by Waigel.
</P>
<P>
The SPD and another opposition party, the Greens, also called
for early election in order to end a government "drama". 
</P>
</TEXT>
