<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Leone's Junta Clamps Curfew in Freetown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The military Junta in Sierra
Leone has ordered a curfew from 10:00 P.M. till 6:00 A.M. in an
attempt to improve the security situation in the capital
Freetown.
</P>
<P>
The state radio, which announced the curfew Tuesday night, also
said the military government would take a number of touch
measures to crack down on possible trouble makers, with the
possibility of offenders to be shot on site.
</P>
<P>
The offenders include those who are caught harassing people
going about their businesses. The use of family personnel by
civilians wishing to settle personal scores is also prohibited.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, civilians caught in security fatigues will be dealt
with according to law, a report reaching here said today.
</P>
<P>
A public relations officer of the Armed Forces Revolutionary
Council (AFRC), the current highest governing body in Sierra
Leone, was quoted as saying that the curfew was imposed to bring
back facility to the business community and allow people to go
about their routine.
</P>
<P>
a source in the defense ministry confirmed that the new orders
are meant to stop the activities of people who have been causing
discomfort to civilians and opposing AFRC functionaries.
</P>
<P>
The tough moves were announced in the wake of a banned "March
for Democracy" called by the National Union of Sierra Leone
students to protest the May 25 coup in which the military seized
power.
</P>
<P>
A student was killed and 35 others were arrested by heavily
armed security forces during Monday's demonstration.
</P>
<P>
The curfew, the first since a similar brief restriction
imposed when the Junta came to power, was justified by military
sources as necessary because of "the current security situation".
</P>
<P>
Sources said the curfew also restricted river traffic for fear
of an attack by the militia from the river.
</P>
<P>
The Junta had received intelligence reports that the Kamajors,
traditional hunters loyal to ousted President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah,
were planning a sea-borne attack on Freetown next week, they
said.
</P>
<P>
"Any boat violating the ban will be seized and its owner
arrested," the state radio said.
</P>
<P>
"We would go as far as to sink any boat which violates the
order," a Sierra Leonean navy officer was quoted as saying.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970821.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Urges U.S. to Address Comprehensive Political </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa today urged the U.S. to address the larger political
aspects of the Mideast peace process rather than be confined to
the Israeli security concern.
</P>
<P>
"Time is now ripe for resuming the political issues of the
peace march," Moussa told reporters.
</P>
<P>
If U.S. Mideast Peace Coordinator Dennis Ross stated that he
succeeded in resuming Palestinian-Israeli security coordination,
"the coming step is to address the political aspect of the problem
namely the implementation of the Oslo agreements in order to
maintain the peace march," he said.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said Washington's ideas should include halting the
"unilateral measures" such as the settlement activities,
implementing the signed agreements regarding the redeployment of
troops from occupied territories and the immediate resumption of
final status talks.
</P>
<P>
Ross' latest tour to the region to restart the peace talks
early this month was focused on Israel's security concerns, also
in preparation for a mission to the region by U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright in September.
</P>
<P>
Albright, in a speech launching the new U.S. initiative on
August 12, said her mission would focus on the thorny political
issues of the peace process, including the Jewish settlement
question and the final status of the Palestinian territories.
</P>
<P>
Israel has insisted the Palestinian National Authority root out
the extremists and arrest some 200 wanted Islamic activists as a
condition for resuming the peace process and lifting sanctions
imposed on Palestinian areas after the July 30 Jerusalem bombings
which killed 16 people.
</P>
<P>
But the PNA in its part insisted that full security cooperation
can only resume when Israeli lifts the sanctions and implements
signed peace agreements.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian minister also condemned the Israeli attacks in the
southern Lebanese port city of Saida on Monday, that killed nine
civilians and wounded 43 others, in the bloodiest attacks since
the end of a major Israeli offensive in April 1996.
</P>
<P>
"Lebanon and its southern part in particular are threatened to
be occupied by Israel," Moussa warned, reiterating Egypt's
denunciation of the Israeli presence in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
About 2,000 Israeli troops, supported by its ally South
Lebanese Army (SLA), have held a border occupation in a
self-declared "security zone" in south Lebanon since 1985, in
defiance of U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Israeli army spokesman denied Israeli troops were behind the
attacks, which violated an April 1996 cease-fire accord that bans
combatants from targeting civilians or launching attacks from
civilian areas. The SLA was reportedly responsible for the
Monday attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
