<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Losses 12 Million Tons of Harvested Grain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Russia has been losing grain
harvest with losses caused by fractured grain estimated at 12
million tons, the Itar-Tass news agency reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Russian Agriculture Ministry said one of the reasons for
grain losses is the shortage of agricultural machinery. At least
136,000 combine harvesters are needed to complete harvesting
campaign on time and with minimal losses.
</P>
<P>
However, many of the combine harvesters available today are
overused, and insufficient financing of rural areas causes
problems both in overhaul of agricultural machinery and the
shortage of new combine harvesters with only 3,000 new pieces of
agricultural machinery bought this year.
</P>
<P>
Another reason is that in many areas which have no oil
processing enterprises agricultural machinery stands idle because
of the absence of gasoline and diesel fuel.
</P>
<P>
According to Russian Agriculture Minister Viktor Khlystun,
several rail oil tanks which were prepared to be exported had to
be returned to Russia. But it is not immediately clear whether
this fuel has actually reached rural areas.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, foreign entrepreneurs seek to take advantage
of this situation as well.
</P>
<P>
Turkish businessmen offer their own combine harvesters and
fuel. The main rice-cultivating area in the Kuban region,
Krasnoarmeisky, ordered 40 combine harvesters to be provided by
Turkish businessmen.
</P>
<P>
In Siberia heavy rains and strong winds which swept the
territory of the Sverdlovsk region in August. Grain has been
actually harvested on 3,000 out of 597,000 hectares because there
are only 22 combine harvesters provided with a stem-raising
mechanism.
</P>
<P>
Last year, five million tons of grain were left unharvested
because of a spell of cold weather. 
</P>
</TEXT>
