<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-20 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Minister Rejects Expansion of War in South </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Foreign Minister David
Levy today rejected a hawkish idea to expand aggression in south
Lebanon, according to a report of the state-run Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters, Levy explained that it was not the time
for everyone to raise the ideas that could only mean continuing
the flare-up.
</P>
<P>
Levy, who was regarded as a dove in the hardline Likud-led
coalition, was apparently referring to an idea raised by his
cabinet colleague Science Minister Michael Eitan to expand the
Israeli self-styled "Security Zone", which covers about 1,000
square kilometers.
</P>
<P>
Eitan argued that a wider "Security Zone" would distance
Hezbollah and its Katyusha rockets from the Israeli border. The
"Security Zone" was set up in January 1985.
</P>
<P>
Levy declared that the current government's policy is not to
push the war beyond the "Security Zone." He added that Israel does
not want a further deterioration, but is doing everything possible
to calm down the situation in the north.
</P>
<P>
Levy's stand was nodded by unidentified defense sources, said
the report. They argued that an exlargement of the war would not
prevent Katyushas from reaching Israel, as they know that the
Lebanese guerrilla group would obtain new Katyushas with a greater
range of 40 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
To expand the "Security Zone" would lead to a confrontation
with Syria, and U.S. and international condemnation, said the
defense sources.
</P>
<P>
Over 80 Katyushas were reportedly fired by Hezbollah
Tuesday. Some 45 landed inside Israel, most in open
fields. However, despite the heavy attack, injuries and damage
were light.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah, or Party of God, claimed responsibility for the
attack, saying that it was in response to the shelling by the
pro-Israeli South Lebanon Army of Sidon Monday, which killed at
least six civilians and wounded 35 others. 
</P>
</TEXT>
