<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Namibia Refuses to Arrest Former Rwandese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The Namibian government
has said it cannot yet arrest a former Rawandese minister Andre
Rwamakuba who is wanted back home to answer charges of the 1994
genocide.
</P>
<P>
The Southern African Broadcasting Association today quoted a
Namibian official statement as saying that Rwamakuba is a free
man who is entitled to work in Namibia until the United Nations
International War Tribunal on Rwanda requests his arrest.
</P>
<P>
The statement said Rwamakuba is protected under Namibian
constitution, which states a person is innocent until found
guilty by a court of law.
</P>
<P>
Rwamakuba was arrested by the Namibian authorities in 1995.
But he was later released on the instruction of the international
tribunal on Rwanda due to lack of evidence.
</P>
<P>
The Rwandese government officially approached Namibian
President Sam Nujoma's administration on Monday to have the
former minister extradited.
</P>
<P>
The Rwandese government accused Rwamakuba of helping to incite
the 1994 ethnic violence which led to the death of at least one
million people, mostly the Tutsi minority by the Hutu majority.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda and Namibia reportedly have agreed during talks in
Windhoek to hand over Rwamakuba to the international tribunal if
it asks for his arrest.
</P>
<P>
Namibia and Rwanda have no extradition treaty between them.
</P>
</TEXT>
