<HEADLINE> Israeli Labor Leader Confirms Having Sent Letter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The leader of Israel's opposition
Labor Party Ehud Barak today confirmed here that he had sent a
letter to Syrian President Hafez al-Assad via an Arab Israeli
parliament deputy who visited Damascus last week, reported Agence
France-Presse (AFP).
</P>
<P>
After a meeting with French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine,
Barak said that he asked Assad to "do all he can so that the
Syrian-Israeli negotiations can resume in the interests of the two
peoples," according to AFP.
</P>
<P>
Barak also said in the letter that "an exchange of messages is
better than an exchange of threats" between Israel and Syria.
</P>
<P>
The Arab Israeli Labor deputy Saleh Tarif, who made a visit to
Syria last week, said that Barak had told Assad that Syria can
make peace with Israel if the Labor Party returns to power,
because the latter will observe the commitments made by former
Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin.
</P>
<P>
Barak was on a "half-private visit" in France, during which
he had a meeting with Prime Minister Lionel Jospin on Monday.
</P>
<P>
During their meeting with Barak, the French Socialist Party
officials expressed their worry over the "continuous degradation
of the situation in the Middle East," said AFP.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Barak said that he thinks an eventual withdrawal
of Israeli troops from Golan Heights depends on "the depth,
quality and nature" of peace to be realized between Israel and
Syria.
</P>
<P>
The government of Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu places the
unilateral security considerations of Israel above any withdrawal
of Israeli troops from Golan Heights. 
</P>
