<HEADLINE> Cypriot President Urges UN to Act </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides has urged the U.N. Security Council to take action if the
Turkish side continues to be intransigent on Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after a cabinet meeting today, Clerides said "no
progress on the Cyprus issue can be achieved if the Security
Council does not decide its stance, should Turkish intransigence
continue."
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that both Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash and Ankara are intransigent in their positions.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on reports that the U.S. and Britain refrained
from blaming the Turkish side for the deadlock in the Cyprus
peace talks, the president said that both countries "want the
negotiating process to continue and avoid anything that may
create a problem."
</P>
<P>
However, Clerides called on the U.S. and Britain to "call a
spade a spade" and present a true picture of what has happened
during the past two rounds of U.N.-led talks.
</P>
<P>
"They are being misled if they believe they can bring Denktash
back to the negotiating table by avoiding to present a clear
picture," Clerides said.
</P>
<P>
The second round of direct talks between Greek and Turkish
Cypriot sides which were held in Glion, Switzerland, ended in
deadlock last Friday, because Denktash insisted the European Union
(EU) postpone or reverse its decision to begin accession talks
with Cyprus scheduled in early 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriot leader accused the EU of "throwing a
bombshell" in the Cyprus peace process and threatened that he
would not attend any further talks if the EU report "Agenda 2000"
is ratified in December.
</P>
<P>
The report reaffirmed an EU Council decision in March 1995, to
begin membership talks with Cyprus six months after the conclusion
of the Intergovernmental Conference.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus issue has remained unresolved since 1974 when the
island was divided after Turkish troops invaded and took over
the northern third of the island in the wake of a failed coup
seeking union with Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
