<HEADLINE> Turkey Urges EU to Reconsider Its Cyprus Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Turkey today urged the European
Union (EU) to reconsider its accession talks with the Cypriot
government, stressing that it has an important bearing on the
settlement of the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a weekly press conference here, Turkish Foreign
Ministry Spokesman Sermet Atacanli reiterated that Turkey's stance
on the Cyprus problem has remained unchanged, adding that it
is the EU itself should reconsider its Cyprus policy.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the second round of Cyprus peace talks which
ended in Switzerland last weekend, Atacanli quoted Turkish Cypriot
leader Rauf Denktash as saying that no process would be made
unless the EU dropped its plan of membership negotiations with
the Cypriot government.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations-sponsored talks collapsed as Denktash and
Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides failed to make any concessions
on some key issues.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission has planned to start accession talks
with Cyprus early next year, triggering strong opposition from
both Turkey and Turkish Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
"In such an environment, there is no reason to wait for any
other concrete development," said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Turkey itself, which has made efforts for years for full EU
membership, was greatly angered by a European Commission report
which includes Cyprus into the ranks of prospective candidates.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus problem has remained unresolved since 1974 when the
Turkish troops invaded and took over the northern third of the
eastern Mediterranean island in the wake of an abortive coup
seeking for union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Both Greece and Turkey station thousands of troops on the
divided island to respectively protect Greek Cypriots and Turkish
Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
The U.N and international community have been trying for
decades to reunited this divided nation through peaceful
dialogues, but no tangible results have been achieved so far.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
