<HEADLINE> Iran Has New Liberal Cultural Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Ataollah Mohajerani, the most
outspoken liberal member of the proposed cabinet of Iran's
President Mohammad Khatami, won vote of confidence from a
conservative-dominated Parliament today.
</P>
<P>
The Khatami-proposed minister of culture and Islamic guidance
received 144 votes from 266 members of the Parliament, who
listened for 16 hours to arguments by liberals and conservatives
for and against Khatami's choice for the custodian of Iran's
cultural affairs.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Culture and Islamic Guidance (MCIG) is one of
the most sensitive and important department which has been long
directly controlled by Iranian Supreme Leader Ali Khamenei.
</P>
<P>
Now, this ministry has turned from hardliners' hands to hands
of the liberal camp headed by moderate ex-president Akbar Hashemi
Rafsanjani, observers said.
</P>
<P>
Mohajerani, who addressed the parliament for 48 minutes,
defended his liberal viewpoints and his record in Iranian
journalism which includes writing articles in liberal daily
Ettela'at in defense of freedom of expression.
</P>
<P>
He vowed to completely transform MCIG if elected and attacked
the conservative policies of the former MCIG minister Mostafa
Mirsalim.
</P>
<P>
"I am opposed to almost all of the prevalent methods in MCIG
and present managers will have to adjust themselves (if I am
elected)," he added.
</P>
<P>
In his concluding remark to the Parliament, Khatami fully
backed Mohajerani, calling him one of the "greatest assets" of the
Islamic Republic.
</P>
<P>
Khatami asserted that the liberal views of his proposed MCIG
minister were exactly what people voted for when they chose him
Iran's president on May 23.
</P>
<P>
The 54-year-old president himself served as the MCIG minister
between 1980 and 1992.
</P>
<P>
Ataollah Mohajerani was born in 1954 in Arak, some 288
kilometers south of the capital city of Tehran. He received PhD
from Teacher's Training University in Tehran and is well-versed in
English, Arabic and Urdu.
</P>
<P>
Between 1984 and 1985, he served as Iran's Cultural Attache to
Pakistan. Between 1985 and 1989, he served as Deputy Premier for
Parliamentary and Legal Affairs. From 1989 up to now he has been
Vice-President for Parliamentary and Legal Affairs.
</P>
<P>
Mohajerani is married to a feminist journalist Jamileh
Kadivar who ran for Parliament from her hometown of Shiraz in
1995 but failed to get elected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
