<HEADLINE> Israeli Warplanes Raid Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Israeli warplanes today raided at
least three areas in Lebanon in a bid to warn the Lebanese
government to curb Hezbollah's military activity againist Israel,
the Lebanese Orient Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Six Israeli warplanes blasted a Hezbollah's training base in
the east sector of Lebanon's eastern Bekka Valley at 10:30 am
(7:30 GMT), injuring two children.
</P>
<P>
Half an hour later, Israeli fighter jets fired air-to-surface
missiles at the village of Toufahtr near Saida, about 40
kilometers south of the capital city of Beirut. The missiles
landed at a garden near an outpost of Lebanese army without
causing any casualties.
</P>
<P>
Israeli troops launched the third air raid at 11:30 am (8:30
GMT), destroying an electric pole in the Huroup area near Saida,
cutting off the electric supply for several villages nearby.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the Israeli army said that the Lebanese
government should take measures to curb the military activities of
Hezbollah, or Party of God, especially the firing of Katyusha
rockets at Israel.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese media said that the Israeli air raid today was
apparently a reaction to the Katyusha rockets fired by Hezbollah
Tuesday at northern Israeli panhandle of Galilee, causing two
injuries and some damage.
</P>
<P>
The Hezbollah's attack was a response to the shelling by the
South Lebanese Army, Israeli militia ally, on Lebanese port city
of Saida which killed nine people and wounded 43 others on
Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
