<HEADLINE> US Asks Syria to Exert Influence on Hezbollah </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 20 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright has asked Syrian Foreign Minister Farouq
al-Shara to try to rein in Lebanon-based Hezbollah guerrillas, and
Shara has promised Syria would do its best to stop the violence
escalating, the State Department said today.
</P>
<P>
"She made clear to him the importance of maximum restraint
being used by all the parties in the field. We have discussed
these matters with the Syrians and Lebanese in the past and regard
them as the right parties to try to influence Hezbollah,"
spokesman James Rubin told reporters.
</P>
<P>
During pre-dawn hours Tuesday, Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak
Mordechai awakened Albright and delivered the stark message,
saying "in no uncertain terms" that Israel would retaliate
"massively" if Hezbollah guerrillas launched another barrage of
Katyusha rockets into northern Israel.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai said Israel was prepared to launch a bombing campaign
throughout Lebanon and possibly Syria if the Katyusha rocket
attacks continued.
</P>
<P>
Albright immediately telephoned Syrian Foreign Minister Shara,
asking Damascus to intervene in the mushrooming crisis.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said, "We understood from that conversation that the
Syrian government was going to do all they could to ensure that
the April 1996 understanding was lived up to and a cycle of
violence was not escalated."
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-brokered understanding banned attacks on civilians but
did not exclude Hezbollah attacking Israeli forces and their
Lebanese allies inside Lebanese territory.
</P>
<P>
Today, Israel's air force launched its biggest attack into
Lebanon for 16 months in retaliation for a Hezbollah rocket attack
on the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said the right forum for stopping the violence was an
international monitoring group of Lebanese, Israeli, Syrian, U.S.
and French officials.
</P>
<P>
The group is expected to meet in Naqura on the Israeli-Lebanese
border later today to discuss complaints from both sides of the
border.
</P>
<P>
The committee was set up after an Israeli offensive in south
Lebanon killed 200 people, mostly civilians, in 1996. It examines
alleged attacks on civilians.
</P>
<P>
"We hope this cycle of violence will not be extended. The
parties did restate that they would uphold the 1996 understanding
and that is what we are going to be talking about (in Naqura),"
Rubin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
