<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most People in China's Tibet to Shake Off Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Chairman of the Tibetan
Association for Cultural Exchange with Foreign Countries Tenzin
said today that an overwhelming majority of the people in China's
autonomous region of Tibet will get rid of poverty and live a
better-off life by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Tenzin, also director of the Chinese Tibetan Song and Dance
Ensemble, was speaking at an informal discussion on Tibet in the
Swiss capital of Bern. Present at the discussion were Chinese
Ambassador to Switzerland Zhou Zizhong, Swiss government
officials, Swiss parliament members, and those interested in
Tibet. The ensemble is in Switzerland to attend the week-long
International Rencounter of Folklore, which began Tuesday in
Fribourg.
</P>
<P>
Tenzin stressed that Tibet has been an integral part of the
Chinese territory since the 12th century. "Under the 46-year rule
of the People's Republic of China, especially since China started
in 1979 to implement the open-door policy architected by its late
senior leader Deng Xiaoping, Tibet, like other provinces in China,
has made a lot of progress and achievements in developing economy,
improving people's living standard, and protecting Tibet's
traditional culture," he said.
</P>
<P>
"To ensure the full development in Tibet, the central
government has provided it with a series of preferential policies
in politics, economy, education and so on," Tenzin said. "Since
the end of 1994, the central government and local governments of
other parts of China have supported Tibet in 62 projects with a
total investment of more than 3.67 billion yuan (about 440 million
U.S. dollars)."
</P>
<P>
In such a pace, Tenzin said, most people in the Tibet
autonomous region will shake off poverty and enjoy a more
comfortable life.
</P>
<P>
"Keeping freedom of religious beliefs is the consistent policy
of the Chinese government, and normal religious activities are
protected by law," Tenzin told those at the discussion. There are
more than 1,700 temples in Tibet and more than 40,000 monks and
nuns staying in the temples, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The Tibetan culture is part of the splendid culture in the
whole of China," he said. "To respect, inherit and develop it is
always the policy being carried out by the central government. All
languages within China are equal, and Tibetan has been widely
taught and better developed."
</P>
<P>
The above-mentioned hard facts, Tenzin said, are strong enough
to reveal the true nature of the rumors about Tibet spread by
certain Western politicians and media, who have been plotting to
separate Tibet from China for centuries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
