<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Ministers Defend Fuel Price Hike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Three major cabinet ministers of
Bangladeshi government today jointly defended the price hike of
petroleum products, saying it would not affect the common people.
</P>
<P>
In a joint press conference, Commerce and Industries Minister
Tofail Ahmed explained that the farmers and lower income urban
groups would not be affected because the prices of the two vital
products, diesel and kerosene, were raised by only 0.25 taka per
liter.
</P>
<P>
The government Monday refixed the prices of all petroleum
products, among which each liter of petrol price rose sharply to
21 taka from 13.70 taka while diesel and kerosene from 12.70 taka
to 12.95 taka, in a bid to keep pace with the international
market.
</P>
<P>
This move, however, triggered sharp reactions among different
political parties and transport circles. The main opposition
Bangladesh Nationalist Party (BNP) had threatened a countrywide
strike on August 24 if the fuel price hike was not withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
Tofail Ahmed called upon the opposition not to politicize the
issue but to realize that the international market price of
petroleum, which the country imports with cash money, has
increased abnormally over the past few years.
</P>
<P>
Energy Minister Muhammad Nooruddin Khan in the press conference
also termed the government decision as "timely and correct" in
view of international market price of fuel.
</P>
<P>
Khan said the international price of petroleum shot up to 33
U.S. dollars per barrel in January this year. But the government
did not raise the price at that time on the consideration that it
might hit hard the people.
</P>
<P>
Instead, it wait to see the price fall in the world market and
increased the local fuel price when the international price is
roughly 24 dollars per barrel now, he added.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister S.A.M.S. Kibria told the press conference that
due to the price hike in the international market, the country had
to bear the burden of 4.5 billion taka (about 101 million dollars)
as revenue loss in the fuel sector every year.
</P>
<P>
He said all past governments had made profit by selling
petroleum products but the present government, taking power in
June last year, is refraining from doing so, because it cares for
the welfare of the people.
</P>
<P>
However, it was also not desirable that the government would
give subsidies to car owners ignoring the interests of the vast
majority of the people, he argued.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
