<HEADLINE> German Company Announces Plan to Sell Russian Missile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 21 (Xinhua) -- A German company said today that it
expects to sign a contract in a few weeks with the Russian
government on selling the uranium from dismantled Russian nuclear
warheads.
</P>
<P>
Nukem, a unit of Germany's RWE group, will market the uranium
through its United States unit, Nukem Inc., based in Connecticut,
in partnership with Cameco of Canada and Cogema of France.
</P>
<P>
Cameco and Cogema will each sell 45 percent of a total of
150,000 tons of the surplus nuclear material, and Nukem plans to
obtain the remaining 10 percent and market it over the next 20
years.
</P>
<P>
A spokeswoman said from Nukem's headquarters at Alzenau, east
of Frankfurt, that the three companies had already signed a
memorandum of agreement with Moscow on the issue, and a final
contract was expected to be ready for signature in a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
The Russian nuclear warheads are being dismantled under a 1993
treaty between the United States and Russia. The uranium and
plutonium in them are too valuable to dump and can be converted
into fuel rods for nuclear power plants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
