<DOCNO> XIE19970821.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belgium Warned of Ozone Depletion Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Meteorologists warned people
today to avoid direct sunlight and possible injury from solar
radiation following reports of ozone depletion Wednesday for the
fourth time this month and the sixth time this year.
</P>
<P>
Elderly people, patients suffering from respiratory problems
and children should not exercise in the open air between high noon
and early night, local television quoted meteorologists as saying.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's readings at two of the country's 22 measuring
stations showed ozone concentration less than 180 micrograms per
cubic meter of air, well below the 360 micrograms set as a
benchmark for alarm.
</P>
<P>
The European Union has instructed its member states to inform
their populace whenever ozone depletion occurs. The two previous
readings of low ozone concentration this year were taken on July
12 and June 4.
</P>
<P>
Meteorologists explained that the frequency of ozone depletion
in this country has been declining compared to figures posted a
couple of years ago.
</P>
<P>
As many as 32 below-benchmark concentrations were reported in
1995 and 20 in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The ozone layer in the atmosphere absorbs solar ultraviolet
radiation, protecting lives on earth from harmful solar radiation
of wavelengths less than 290 nanometers.
</P>
<P>
Waste gases such as automobile exhaust emissions bear the brunt
of the blame for ozone depletion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970821.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rising Oil Output Keeps Prices in Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The world's oil prices will be
kept in check as a result of the rising oil output, according to a
report of the Wall Street Journal today.
</P>
<P>
Although demand for oil has been climbing, the price may be
kept in control for at least a year as a swell of new production
moves into global markets from the North Sea, South America and
Iraq, the paper quoted analysts as saying.
</P>
<P>
Estimates show that at least an extra 1.3 million barrels a day
are slated to start flowing during the next six months from
sources outside the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
(OPEC), which itself has been slowly increasing output, the paper
said.
</P>
<P>
It reported that production projects are being undertaken by
major oil companies -- 249,000 barrels daily from the North Sea,
290,000 barrels a day from Columbia and at least 750,000 barrels
daily from Iraq, as it again starts to pump oil under the auspices
of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Australia and Kazakstan will gush out 100,000
barrels daily. Other oil-producing nations also will set up their
pumping.
</P>
<P>
Some exports predicted that crude oil prices could decline to
17 U.S. dollars or 18 U.S. dollars a barrel in coming months.
</P>
<P>
But the oil increase has no immediate impact on the U.S.
consumers. Motorists have seen gasoline prices at the pump even
jump significantly. Analysts commented that a robust economy has
driven more Americans onto the road this summer.
</P>
<P>
The Paris-based International Energy Agency (IEA) says world
oil production this year, excluding OPEC numbers, will hit 44.7
million barrels a day, 1.17 million barrels more than 1996.
</P>
<P>
Next year, the agency estimates, at least another two million
barrels of oil will be moving into the market daily. And IEA
officials do expect that OPEC members will also increase their
output.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970821.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
