<HEADLINE> Mongolia Keen to Deepen Friendship with China: President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Mongolian President Nachagyn
Bagbandy said here today his country would make efforts to develop
a Mongolian-Chinese friendship oriented toward the coming 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
Bagbandy made the remark during a meeting with visiting Chinese
Vice Premier and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen.
</P>
<P>
The president praised the smooth development of cooperation in
recent years between the two countries in the fields of politics,
trade and economy as well as culture.
</P>
<P>
Noting that China is Mongolia's good neighbor, the president
said to develop friendly cooperation with China would be one of
the firm and steadfast priorities of Mongolia's foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
Qian, who arrived here Tuesday for a four-day official visit,
congratulated Bagbandy on being elected Mongolia's new president
in June. He also conveyed Chinese President Jiang Zemin's
congratulations.
</P>
<P>
Qian said China upholds the independent foreign policy of peace
based on self-reliance.
</P>
<P>
Since Mongolia is an important neighbor of China, developing
Sino-Mongolian friendly relations will not only be in the basic
interest of the two peoples, but also be conducive to the peace
and stability of the region.
</P>
<P>
Qian vowed to continue developing the good-neighborliness and
cooperation between China and its northern neighbor.
</P>
<P>
Bagbandy said Qian's visit, which has promoted mutual
understanding, broadened consensus and strengthened bilateral
cooperation, is of great importance to the further development of
bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Radnasumberlyn Gonchigdorzh, chairman of the
Great Hural, Mongolia's parliament, held talks with Qian on
communication between the two countries' parliaments.
</P>
<P>
Qian said contact between the two legislatures is an important
part of state-to-state relations. He hoped China's National
People's Congress and Mongolia's Great Hural continue to cooperate
in the future.
</P>
<P>
Gonchigdorzh hoped the two countries' legislative bodies and
personnel could further strengthen cooperation and exchange
experience. 
</P>
