<HEADLINE> Kohl Confirms Waigel's Plan to Quit after Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 21 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl today
said he was aware of Finance Minister Theo Waigel's plan to quit
after the general elections in September next year.
</P>
<P>
"I respect his position and understand his decision, especially
since I know he is not tired of serving in office," Kohl said in a
statement released in Bonn.
</P>
<P>
In a radio interview on Tuesday evening, Waigel stunned
political observers by saying he would leave his office should
Kohl's center-right coalition win next year's elections.
</P>
<P>
Waigel, who has served as finance minister in Kohl's
center-right government since April 1989, said he was not tired of
holding the office.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with German ARD television network, Waigel said
he would do his best to fulfil his tasks, including negotiating
the planned tax reform and managing budget.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of Waigel's party, the Christian Social Union,
today said that Waigel had not set the election day as deadline
for his minister term.
</P>
<P>
Waigel, 58, has come under sharp criticism recently for his
hardline management of the government budget and the proposed tax
reform, since Germany is struggling to reduce record high
unemployment and to make the grade in order to join the planned
single European currency, the Euro.
</P>
<P>
Waigel also triggered controversies recently for his suggestion
of a cabinet reshuffle before the general election next year.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Waigel's unexpected remarks in Tuesday's
interview, Rudolf Scharping, parliamentary leader of the main
opposition Social Democratic Party, said it was the "recognition
of defeat" by Waigel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
