<HEADLINE> U.S. Sells Military Aircraft to Algeria, Says Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The United States has sold six
military transport aircraft to Algeria at a price estimated to be
worth several hundred million U.S. dollars, the Arabic daily Al
Hayet reported today.
</P>
<P>
An official from the Clinton administration has confirmed the
deal but refused to reveal the exact cost of the planes or their
types and characteristics, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The planes, produced by the U.S. Gulfstream company, will be
delivered to Algeria via Canada, where they will be equipped with
"information programs in French," it said.
</P>
<P>
Gulfstream estimated the cost of the planes at from 28 to 38
million dollars each.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials said the planes can engage in wars, supervise
frontiers, carry out reconnaissance missions against potential
enemies, and communicate for military purposes.
</P>
<P>
The Algerian government is currently engaged in an all-out war
against Islamic militants who have tried to topple it for six
years.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government and the Algerian government have so far
remained silent on details of the deal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
