<HEADLINE> Scholar: Dalai Lama's Political Position Granted by Central Government (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
He went on to say that the political-religious system was set
up after the Yuan, Ming, and Qing dynasties confirmed the
establishment of the sects of Sakyapa, Phagdru Kagyupa and Gelugpa
respectively.
</P>
<P>
"The system was under the jurisdiction of the central
government, and could not be manipulated by one sect alone. It
affirmed the existence of the three regimes of the sects, and also
affirmed the absolute leadership of the central government over
Tibet's local governments," he said.
</P>
<P>
Chang pointed out that in the first half of this century,
although the system was under the sole direct control of the Dalai
Lama, the international community agreed that Tibet was a
political entity under Chinese sovereignty instead of an
independent country.
</P>
<P>
At that time, the title of the Dalai Lama remained
unchanged. "If the Dalai Lama were called Gyatso Lama, he would be
worth nothing," Chang said.
</P>
<P>
He said that after 1840, Tibet along with the rest of China had
become the chief target of aggressive foreign powers and it was
gradually falling into a semi-colonial state.
</P>
<P>
"Some people have no regard for the historical background of
China and blatantly distort historical facts in an attempt to
split Tibet from China," he pointed out. 
