<HEADLINE> SDP Urges Exclusion of Taiwan from New Defense Guidelines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Japan's Social Democratic Party
(SDP) reiterated its position today that the Taiwan Straits be
excluded from areas subject to the proposed new Japan-U.S. defense
guidelines, said a report of the Kyodo News Service.
</P>
<P>
The SDP, one of the two allies of the ruling Liberal Democratic
Party (LDP), made the statement at a meeting of policy-makers from
the tripartite ruling camp, which includes the LDP, led by Prime
Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto, the SDP, and New Party Sakigake.
</P>
<P>
The participants agreed to hammer out a common view on the new
guidelines by Friday, but a senior SDP official said it would be
difficult to meet the deadline because of differences between the
SDP and the LDP over the definition of "areas surrounding Japan,"
Kyodo said.
</P>
<P>
The issue of how to define the areas surrounding Japan has been
in the spotlight since Chief Cabinet Secretary Seiroku Kajiyama
said in a Sunday TV talk show that the new defense guidelines
would cover emergencies in the Taiwan Straits.
</P>
<P>
Kajiyama's remarks triggered strong criticism from China as
they signaled an attempt to interfere in China's internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
The new guidelines are intended to replace the 1978
Japan-U.S. defense cooperation guidelines, paving the way for
Japan to provide a broad range of logistic and noncombatant
support to the U.S. military in case of emergencies "in areas
surrounding Japan." 
</P>
</TEXT>
