<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Defamation Suit: QC Carman Makes Final Submission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Queen's Counsel (QC) George
Carman made his final submissions today in the High Court of
Singapore on the fourth day of the defamation suit brought by
ruling People's Action Party (PAP) leaders against opposition
Workers' Party chief J.B. Jeyaretnam.
</P>
<P>
According to a Singapore television report, Mr. Carman, hired
by Mr. Jeyaretnam, maintained that an ordinary person would not
have concluded that Mr. Jeyaretnam was guilty of defamation by his
remarks at an election rally last January.
</P>
<P>
The PAP leaders, including Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong and
Senior Minister Lee Kuan Yew, are suing Mr. Jeyaretnam for telling
a Workers' Party election campaign rally on January 1 this year
that his team-mate in the Cheng San Group Representation
Constituency, lawyer Tang Liang Hong, had just placed before him
two reports the latter made to the police against the Prime
Minister and his team.
</P>
<P>
The PAP leaders claimed the words Jeyaretnam used implied that
they had conspired to commit criminal defamation against Mr. Tang
by labeling him an anti-Christian, anti-English educated Chinese
chauvinist.
</P>
<P>
Mr. Carman said today that the remarks were not capable of
bearing the meaning which the Prime Minister's lawyers put on them
- that he is guilty of criminal offenses.
</P>
<P>
Mr. Carman also said that Mr. Goh's claim was an orchestrated
one and Mr. Jeyaretnam had not inflicted any damage on the PAP
leaders.
</P>
<P>
He added that both Mr. Goh and the senior minister had
themselves inflicted the damage when they released the contents of
the police report to the local media.
</P>
<P>
Mr. Carman submitted that although the meaning of the remarks
as intended by the public was irrelevant, the court must take into
account their context. In this case, he said, it was political in
nature at an election rally.
</P>
<P>
In the heat of battle between parties, Mr. Carman said such
statements could be taken with a pinch of salt.
</P>
<P>
Mr. Jeyaretnam's statement, said his lawyer, was also one
without embellishment or comment. He was reporting a true fact and
this, Mr. Carman said, cannot give rise to defamation.
</P>
<P>
Turning to damages, Mr. Carman submitted that the issue should
never arise in this case. However, he added that the prime
minister had already been fully vindicated and compensated over
his libel suit against Mr. Tang.  
</P>
</TEXT>
