<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Consumption of Petro Products Up 1.2 Percent in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 21 (Xinhua) -- European Union's (EU)
consumption of petroleum products rose in 1996 by 1.2 percent to
544.8 million tons, a Eurostat press release reported today.
</P>
<P>
The increase was pumped up mainly by a 5.3 percent increase in
the consumption of kerosene and jet fuel and a 4.9 percent rise in
gas and diesel oil.
</P>
<P>
Consumption of motor fuels, however, decreased once again
though slightly by 0.2 percent, while residual fuel oil fell
substantially by 5.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Sweden led the 15-nation union with a 15.6 percent increase in
petroleum product consumption, whereas Portugal was on the other
end of the consumption scale, with a 6.3 percent decrease in
consumption.
</P>
<P>
Other EU countries with increased oil consumption included
Belgium, Denmark and Greece, with a growth of 12.6 percent, 8.1
percent and 7.1 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Joining Portugal in a declining amount of consumption were
Finland, with a 6.2 percent drop, Spain, 4.0 percent, Italy and
the Netherlands, each with a 2.6 percent fall, said the latest
report from the Luxembourg-based Eurostat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
