<DOCNO> XIE19970821.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iron Age House Discovered In Britain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The remains of one of the best-
preserved Iron Age houses ever discovered has been found in
Britain, The Daily Telegraph reported today.
</P>
<P>
The house, located at Old Scatness, in north-eastern Britain,
has a corbelled stone roof and is believed to date from around the
time of Christ, Alan Braby, who found the house, said.
</P>
<P>
The entire structure of the house, which includes the roof, is
complete. Archaeologist Val Turner said the discovery is seen as
the most significant since "Jarlshof," a multi-layered
archaeological site just a mile from Old Scatness.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, another Iron Age building, with yellow clay still
plastered on the walls, and a wheelhouse with the remains of an
iron pot containing the bones of an uneaten fish, has also been
found. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
