<HEADLINE> Four EU States Use Unleaded Fuels for All Cars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Austria, Denmark, Finland and
Sweden are the only four European Union member states where all
cars used only clean, unleaded fuel in 1996, a Eurostat report
said today.
</P>
<P>
The four countries also used unleaded fuels for all their cars
in the preceding year as well.
</P>
<P>
Spain is the EU member where unleaded fuels were used least.
Just a little more than a third of the country's cars used the
cleaner fuels, the most recent Eurostat report said.
</P>
<P>
It said consumption of unleaded fuel by cars in Greece,
Portugal and Italy is also below the 50 percent mark.
</P>
<P>
More and more people are being encouraged to use unleaded fuel
in the European Union where the population is becoming
increasingly sensitive about the environment.
</P>
<P>
All 15 member states of the union registered increases to
various extent of consumption of cleaner fuels in the past year
compared to 1995.
</P>
<P>
The union, as a whole, saw an increase of five percentage
points to around 72 percent of consumption in unleaded fuels by
cars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
