<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Maps Out Administrative Reform Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Japan's Administrative Reform
Council today agreed on a blueprint to trim the current 22
ministries and agencies into a cabinet office and 12 ministries,
the local media reported.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached after four days of intensive
discussions by a 15-member panel that was headed by Prime Minister
Ryutaro Hashimoto.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, the current Prime Minister's Office and the
Management and Coordination Agency will be combined into a cabinet
office, which is expected to deal with such things as
macro-economics, science and technology, gender equality and
disaster prevention.
</P>
<P>
Six new ministries will be set up by reorganizing the current
agencies and ministries, including a general affairs ministry, a
national land development ministry and others. The Justice and
Foreign Ministries will remain.
</P>
<P>
The panel members continue to disagree on whether the Defense
Agency should be turned into a ministry, though they have agreed
to carry the differing opinions in a report scheduled for
completion by September 3.
</P>
<P>
Upon its release, the report will be examined by the ruling
Liberal Democratic Party and its two allies, the Social Democratic
Party and New Party Sakigake.
</P>
<P>
The Administrative Reform Council was initiated last November.
</P>
</TEXT>
