<HEADLINE> China to Strengthen Anti-Prostitution Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 21 (Xinhua) -- China's Ministry of Public
Security on Wednesday issued a notice requiring police departments
nationwide to further step up the crackdown on prostitution and
pornographic activities.
</P>
<P>
According to the notice, more police operations should be
planned to clean up a few places of prostitution, including
Karaoke bars, dance halls, sauna and massage parlors, and roadside
stores.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, big efforts should also be made to improve the
supervision of the migrant workers. Houses should never be allowed
to rent for prostitution activities and, otherwise their owners
should be brought to justice in accordance with law.
</P>
<P>
Lawbreakers should be punished according to the relevant laws
and regulations, said the notice, which also stressed that anyone
involved in the procurement or solicitation of prostitutes faces
still heavier punishment.
</P>
<P>
China has launched a series of anti-prostitution campaigns
since early this year and the efforts so far have paid off.
</P>
