<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Breast Screening To Reduce Deaths In Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- A national breast screening
program is being spread out in Australia which was believed to
reduce breast cancer deaths by 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
"Since the program got going in 1991, we have seen a small
reduction in mortality, we estimate the downturn is in the order
of four to five percent, but it is going to be five to ten years
before we start to see the real impact of the program," Bruce
Armstrong, director of the Cancer Council's information center in
New South Wales.
</P>
<P>
While addressing the first national breast cancer screening
conference held here today, Armstrong said, it is generally
accepted that you will see a 30 percent drop, if you get a better
than 70 percent participation rate in screening in the 50 to 74
year age group.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Jill Cockburn told the conference that the program was on
track, with 61 percent of the target age group having being
screened by Breast Screen Australia or elsewhere in the past two
years.
</P>
<P>
Among women aged 40 to 49 years, who are not targeted but can
get a free screen, 23 percent had a screening mammogram in the
past two years.
</P>
<P>
"These figures are very reassuring and I think we can now do
some more targeted recruiting to attract that group of women who
don't believe themselves to be at risk," Cockburn said.
</P>
<P>
Breast Screen Australia has performed two million screens
during the past six years finding cancer less than one percent of
women.
</P>
<P>
Breast cancer claims 2500 lives every year in Australia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
