<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scholar: Dalai Lama's Political Position Granted by Central Government (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The fact that the Dalai Lama's
political status was granted by the central government is proof
that Tibet is an inseparable part of China, an established Chinese
scholar has claimed.
</P>
<P>
Chang Fengxun, a senior research fellow from the prestigious
Chinese Academy of Social Sciences, said here today that the two
issues of the Tibetan political-religious system and the status of
the Dalai Lama in Tibet have not only evolved from regional and
ethnic factors, but also are closely tied with the history of the
motherland.
</P>
<P>
"Nevertheless, in the second half of this century, some people
offered different explanations about these situations, and some
people even associate them with sovereignty and human
rights. These explanations are not in accordance with historical
facts," Chang said in a report at the ongoing Beijing Seminar on
Tibetan Studies.
</P>
<P>
Some 130 foreign and Chinese scholars are attending the meeting.
</P>
<P>
According to Chang, the Dalai Lama was originally one of the
many successors of incarnate lamas of the Gelugpa sect of Tibetan
Buddhism. He was neither the "hierarch" of all the sects of
Tibetan Buddhism, nor the "leader" of Tibet's political-religious
system.
</P>
<P>
The Dalai Lama did not have any connection with Tibet's
political-religious system until 1653, when the Qing Dynasty
(1644-1911) gave the title of Dalai Lama to Lozang Gyatso, the
fifth successor of the Gelugpa, Chang noted.
</P>
<P>
"It is clear that the Dalai Lama's political position was
granted by the central government," he stressed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970821.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN, ECOWAS to Resolve on S. Leone Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Security
Council said it will work in concert with the Economic
Community of West African States (ECOWAS) to compel the military
junta in Sierra Leone to return to the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
The council will consult ECOWAS leaders who are scheduled to
meet next week to work out a common strategy, according to the
council President John Weston after the 15-member body met with
the UN scribe's special representative for Sierra Leone Berhann
Dinka on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Weston's words came after ECOWAS Chairman General Sani
Abacha's visit to Cote d'Ivoire and Guinea to canvass for common
position among the sub-regional body towards resolving the crisis
in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Abacha, who is Nigeria's head of state, reportedly said during
his trip on Monday that a military option was inevitable since
the junta had remained intransigent to pressures by the
international community to reinstate the ousted civilian
government of the country.
</P>
<P>
In this regard, the key objective of the Security Council now
is to ensure that it is speaking and acting with the same voice
as ECOWAS ministers, Weston said, quoted by a report reaching
here today.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Weston noted, they would be insisting on UN's
earlier objection to the junta's decision to remain in power.
</P>
<P>
"We want to make clear once again our condemnation of the
violence in the country and our insistence that there should be
freedom of movement and access for humanitarian agencies," he
affirmed.
</P>
<P>
"There is need to be close in consultation with the ECOWAS
group of foreign ministers over the next few days so as to ensure
that any decision we take will be with the full knowledge of what
the ECOWAS group themselves have decided," said the council
president.
</P>
<P>
Whatever measures the council then adopts will reinforce its
efforts as well as that of ECOWAS, he added.
</P>
<P>
Since the coup took place in Sierra Leone on May 25, the
council has issued three statements, condemning the coup and
urging the junta to hand over power to the toppled government led
by President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah. 
</P>
</TEXT>
