<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> C'wealth Attitude Determines Nigeria's Membership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria has said its continued
membership of the commonwealth will depend on how the 52-member
organization redresses the perceived wrong done to the country
two years ago.
</P>
<P>
According to Foreign Minister Tom Ikimi, a major criterion for
determining whether Nigeria would remain within the fold is "the
overall perception of whether the association is not being
derailed from the original goals and objectives", local media
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to members of the country's long-term planning body,
Vision 2010 Committee, on Wednesday in th capital Abuja, Ikimi
urged the planning body to take a "serious look at the
commonwealth-Nigeria diplomatic impasse on the basis of what is
in our best national interest".
</P>
<P>
Nigeria was suspended its membership from the Commonwealth at
the Auckland summit in New Zealand in 1995, prompted by the
execution of Ken Saro-Wiwa and eight of his Ogoni activists.
</P>
<P>
The Commonwealth Ministerial Action Group (CMAG) was set up at
the summit to deal with Nigeria's human rights record.
</P>
<P>
The CMAG, which has visited and talked with Nigeria, is
expected to reconvene in September this year to take a stand on
Nigeria ahead of the Commonwealth summit in Edinburgh, Scotland
in October.
</P>
<P>
It is reported earlier that Nigeria is considering to quit the
Commonwealth in case the organization decides to discharge
Nigeria at the end of its two-year ultimatum for the country to
democratize.
</P>
<P>
Also on Wednesday, Ikimi said despite the problems Nigeria was
facing with the Commonwealth, it had to open another front with
the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
Admitting that "relations between Nigeria and the EU have
dropped to a very low ebb," Ikimi pointed out that the problems
lied in the EU decision "to meddle in our internal affairs".
</P>
<P>
Since the EU has clamped sanctions in areas of renewal of visa
and arms embargo, it is impossible to make contacts at the
highest level between the EU and Nigeria, the foreign minister
said.
</P>
<P>
The EU first imposed limited sanctions on Nigeria in 1993
after the annulment of that year's presidential election. The
sanctions were renewed following the execution of the Nien Ogoni
activists in 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
