<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese President Meets With US Senators in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 21 (Xinhua) -- President Jiang Zemin today told
two visiting US senators that China is ready to work alongside the
US to create a long-term, stable bilateral relationship for the
21st century on the basis of the three Sino-US joint communiques.
</P>
<P>
Jiang made the pledge during a meeting with John McCain,
chairman of the Commerce, Science and Transportation Committee of
the US Senate, and Senator Phil Gramm.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that the two countries share many mutual interests
and have great potentials of cooperation for maintaining world and
regional peace, and promoting global economic prosperity, all of
which has laid a foundation for the steady development of
bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
China values the Sino-US relations very much, the Chinese
leader said. Since the beginning of the year, he added, the two
countries have moved progressively forward in their relationship,
and there have been more exchanges in various fields and their
economic and trade cooperation has grown steadily.
</P>
<P>
Many US congressmen have visited China to date, Jiang said, and
the two countries now have many good opportunities for further
improvement of bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
McCain said that Jiang's upcoming state visit to the US is of
historical significance, and that the American people will welcome
him.
</P>
<P>
And Americans understand how important the positive and stable
US-China relations are, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Gramm called China's rapid economic growth a "miracle", and
said that during the trip, he saw for himself the Chinese people
are living a happy life as a result of the country's economic
development.
</P>
<P>
Both McCain and Gramm pointed out that maintaining the friendly
and cooperative connection between the US and China in the next
century is of profound significance for the people of the two
countries and the world as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Attending the meeting were Mei Zhaorong, president of the
Chinese People's Institute of Foreign Affairs, and Li Zhaoxing,
Chinese Vice-Foreign Minister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
