<HEADLINE> Li Peng: Sino-Malaysian Friendly Ties to Enjoy New </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Chinese Premier Li
Peng today expressed his confidence that the friendly relations
and cooperation between China and Malaysia will experience new and
greater development.
</P>
<P>
"Our two peoples have enjoyed a long history of friendship with
each other and have steadily expanded cooperation in various
fields," Li said at a grand banquet tonight hosted in his honor by
his Malaysian counterpart Mahathir Mohammed.
</P>
<P>
He said both countries, which share identical or similar views
on many international issues, have been in close consultation and
cooperation with each other in international affairs.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese premier praised Malaysia for its active part it has
taken in regional and international affairs, saying "it has upheld
justice in international affairs in defiance of might and worked
for the common development of third world countries, for which we
wish to express our appreciation and admiration."
</P>
<P>
Li, who arrived here earlier today for a four-day friendly
official visit to Malaysia, believed his official talks with
Mahathir tomorrow will be of "great importance to continuous
development of our bilateral relations".
</P>
<P>
The two sides will have an extensive and in-depth exchange of
views on bilateral relations and on regional and international
issues of mutual interest, the Chinese premier said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the world situation, Li said the world today is
moving towards multipolarity, which is conducive to the noble
cause of peace and development.
</P>
<P>
Li spoke highly of the increasing important role that the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) is playing in
regional and international affairs.
</P>
<P>
"China and ASEAN are engaged in fruitful, all-round cooperation
with each other," Li said, pledging that China "would like to make
further efforts together with ASEAN countries to develop a
21st-century-oriented friendly and good-neighborly relationship."
</P>
<P>
Present at tonight's banquet were Li's wife Zhu Lin and senior
Chinese officials who are accompanying Li on the ongoing visit.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the banquet, Li met with Chairman of Maybank Basir
Ahmad and briefed him on China's financial policy and economic
situation.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese premier's last visit to Malaysia was in December
1990. 
</P>
