<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Universiade: Beginning of Success of World Class Athletes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
CATANIA, Sicily, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The last three editions of
World University Games in Sheffield, Buffalo and Fukuoka have proved
to be the beginning of success of many world-class athletes.
</P>
<P>
Derrick Adkins of the United States, who won the 400-meter
hurdles at the 1991 Sheeffield and 1993 Buffalo Universiades, took
the gold medal of the event at the 1996 Atlanta Olympic Games. The
silver medalist at the Olympics is Samuel Matete of Zambia, Adkins'
rival at the Buffalo Universiade.
</P>
<P>
The two hurdlers also finished 1-2 at the 1995 Goteborg
Athletics World Championships.
</P>
<P>
Pole Vaulter Jean Galfione of France finished only third at
Buffalo. But three years later, he cleared 5.92 meters to set a new
Olympic record and won the gold medal at Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
Sun Fuming of China has the similiar story as Galfione. Having
finished third at Fukuoka Universiade, she took the open class title
of women's judo at the Atlanta Olympics one year later.
</P>
<P>
There are many other athletes who benefitted from their
Universiade experiences and surged to stardom. They are Canadian
rower Derek Porter, Belorussian gymnast Vitaly Scherbo, Chinese
swimmer Le Jingyi, Italian Olympic fencing champion Alessandro
Puccini, to name just a few.
</P>
<P>
This time at Sicily, some 6,000 athletes again gathered up to
compete at World Universiade. Three years later at Sydney, many of
them will surely compete at the 2000 Olympic Games and some will
even step onto the podium. 
</P>
</TEXT>
