<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Floods Kill 15, Displace Thousands in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Fifteen people have been killed
and more than 120,000 others are still seeking refugee in
makeshift centers in the flood-stricken northern Philippines, the
country's disaster authorities said today.
</P>
<P>
The National Disaster Coordinating Council (NDCC) said in an
update report that six more deaths were confirmed today in
flood-hit areas, bringing the flood death toll to 15.
</P>
<P>
More than 35,000 families or 127,000 people continued to live
in evacuation centers after being driven out of their homes by the
massive flooding, which hit the country's northern part during the
past two days, the council said.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 6,000 houses have been damaged or destroyed by flood
waters which were triggered by continuous torrential monsoon
rains.
</P>
<P>
The council put agriculture, livestock and infrastructure
losses at an estimated 6 million pesos (200,000 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
In Metro Manila or the national capital area, most evacuees
have returned to their respective houses as flood waters had
already receded.
</P>
<P>
But in its nearby provinces such as Pampanga and Bataan, tens
of thousands of residents are continuing their combat against
flood waters after some river dykes were breached.
</P>
<P>
The departments of social and welfare and health provided today
a total of 2.2 million pesos for medical supplies and other
emergency services to the evacuees and other victims.
</P>
<P>
Most parts of Luzon Island were cloudy today with only
occasional thundershowers after the tail of super typhoon Winnie
ceased to affect the country, according to the National Weather
Bureau. Winnie was blamed for intensifying the usually moderate
southwest monsoon rains.
</P>
<P>
Less rains are expected to fall in Luzon in the next few days
as a new typhoon Luming has already spared the country and is now
roaring northwestward to China, the bureau forecast.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
