<HEADLINE> August May Be Hottest One in Britain's History </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 21 (Xinhua) -- This August may break all records
and become the hottest in Britain's history, the British
Meteorological Office said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Despite the possibility of weekend storms, analysts believe
that August has already experienced enough sunshine for a long
enough period of time to eclipse previous years. Britain had 15
consecutive days above 26.7 degrees Celsius in 1995 and this
record was reached again on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Temperatures in England and Wales in the first half of August
were more than Three degrees Celsius higher than average. In the
southeast, the figure was about five degrees higher.
</P>
<P>
The lowest recorded temperature in London this month has been
14.6 degrees Celsius, but Met Office figures show that the
temperature has climbed to as high as 31.3 degrees Celsius on a
number of occasions this month.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, the mean temperature here was 19.2 degrees Celsius.
This, too, is expected to be surpassed this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
