<HEADLINE> Angola Not to Join Multi-national Force on Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The Angolan government has
decided not to join a multi-national intervention force aimed at
solving the crisis in Congo Brazzaville, the Angolan News Agency
reported today.
</P>
<P>
In a communique issued Wednesday, the Foreign Ministry said
neither of the warring sides in Congo (B) has contacted Angola
over the issue of joining the multi-national force, so the
government has excluded the possibility of joining it.
</P>
<P>
The idea of forming the multi-national intervention force was
put forward by Laurent Kabila, President of Democratic Congo in
Kinshasa last week when he met for talks with Ugandan President
Yoweri Museveni and Rwandan President Pasteur Bizimungu.
</P>
<P>
According to the proposal, the multi-national troops will be
formed by military forces from eastern and central African
countries, which include Angola, Chad, Rwanda, Burundi, the
Central African Republic, Congo (K) and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
While denying the possibility of joining the multi-national
force, the communique said the Angolan government fully supports
the effort of mediation over the Congo (B) conflict initiated by
Gabonese President El Hadj Omar Bongo and hopes a political
agreement on reconciliation would be reached between the warring
sides.
</P>
<P>
Fighting broke out in Brazzaville in early June between forces
loyal to President Pascal Lissouba and the militia of former
President Sassou Nguesso, killing over 3,000 people and
displacing many more.
</P>
<P>
Angolan President Dos Santos expressed his support to the
peace initiative mapped out by Omar Bongo, when he met with the
visiting envoy of the Gabonese president at the weekend. 
</P>
</TEXT>
