<HEADLINE> DHAKA to Revise Export Target at 5 Billion Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Dhaka, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's export target for the
current fiscal year (1997-98) is likely to be re-fixed at five
billion U.S. dollars, 0.12 billion less than the original target,
official sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
In view of some problems relating to garment and frozen foods
to the European market, the Commerce Ministry would favor an
export target not more than five billion dollars, said the
sources.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, an export target of 5.12 billion dollars was
contemplated for the current fiscal year. However, some exporters
sounded a caution against the "unrealistic" target. They said
failure to reach a set target not only damages country's image
abroad but also puts the government in an embarrassing situation
at home.
</P>
<P>
In the proposed export target for the current fiscal year,
earnings from ready made garment (RMG) and knitwear are to cover
about 70 percent, frozen food 6 percent and leather 4.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Given a disturbed situation for the knitwear products and
frozen foods in the western market due to the restriction by
European Union, export market analysts have cast doubt as to
whether it would be wise or prudent to set the targets.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the shipment of very poor quality and
short-measured leather has also hit some European importers, there
was a meticulous thought on fixing export targets for these items
in the prevailing situation, they said.
</P>
<P>
The export target for 1996-97 fiscal year was fixed at 4.38
billion dollars and the achievement was 4.41 billion dollars.
Among which, the export earnings of the RMG and the knitwear
sector accounted over 66 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
