<HEADLINE> Publication of Tibetan Studies Booms in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Since the founding of new China
in 1949, publishing houses across the country have printed over
2,000 kinds of books on Tibetan studies, most of which were
published in the 1980s and 1990s.
</P>
<P>
The Bibliography on Tibetan Studies in China lists 1,517 kinds
of books on Tibetan studies published by more than 200 publishing
houses from October 1949 to December 1991, including 674 Tibetan
books, 821 Chinese books and 22 English books.
</P>
<P>
Since 1992, nearly 1,000 books on Tibetan studies have been
published, according to Xie Shujing, who works in the National
Library of China and is attending the ongoing 1997 Beijing Seminar
on Tibetan Studies.
</P>
<P>
She said that the bibliography has become a necessary reference
book for researchers on Tibetan studies, and that the boom of
publications has revealed China's esteem for the Tibetan culture.
</P>
<P>
The 1950s and 1980s were the two publishing high points for
books on Tibetan studies, which cover varied fields such as
Tibetan language and writing, geography, literature, arts,
politics, economy, history, astronomy, medicine, agricultural
science, philosophy, education and biology.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1980s, the publishing houses have reprinted some
ancient books. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970821.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
