<HEADLINE> Sino-Portuguese JLG to Hold Talks on Archives Transfer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The Sino-Portuguese Joint Liaison
Group (JLG) will hold a specialized meeting next week to discuss
the transfer of archives in Macao, JLG officials announced here
today.
</P>
<P>
Han Zhaokang, chief representative of the Chinese side of the
JLG, told reporters after a four-hour closed-door meeting with his
 Portuguese counterpart that the two sides have agreed that the
meeting will be held on August 28.
</P>
<P>
Today's meeting was the first formal one between the two chiefs
 after Han assumed office early this month, succeeding Guo Jiading
 as the third chief of the Chinese side of the JLG.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese side has insisted that a special working panel be
established for the transfer of archives," Han said. With
specialized discussion on hand, it is up to both sides to decide
whether they still need to set up such a panel, he added.
</P>
<P>
Antonio Santana Carlos, the Portuguese chief representative,
described today's meeting as "friendly and smooth", saying that he
 hopes consensus would be reached on certain questions soon.
</P>
<P>
At today's meeting, the two sides discussed such topics as
legal cooperation, Macao renewal of member status of some
international conventions, contracts whose term run beyond 1999 in
 Macao, and air agreements Macao has signed with foreign countries
 and regions.
</P>
<P>
The JLG holds three plenary sessions a year in Beijing, Macao
and Lisbon alternately. Both chiefs also meet regularly to discuss
 issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
Han said today's meeting helped both chiefs know each other
better.
</P>
<P>
"It is our common wish to continue friendly cooperation, and to
 work constructively in the remaining two years and four months,"
Han said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
