<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China To Issue Additional 40 Billion Yuan of Treasury Bonds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 21 (Xinhua) -- China plans to issue an
additional 40 billion yuan (about 4.82 billion US dollars) in
certificate bonds beginning on September 1, the Ministry of
Finance announced today in a circular.
</P>
<P>
The new issue will be in three-year bonds with an annual coupon
rate of 9.18 percent, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
It will increase the nation's three-year certificate bonds
volume to 163 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The bonds cannot be listed or traded at the stock market, the
ministry said, and the individual investors can buy the bonds from
the country's five biggest state-owned commercial banks -- the
Industrial and Commercial Bank of China, the Agricultural Bank of
China, the Construction Bank of China, the Bank of China, the
Communications Bank of China -- or from treasury-bond operations
affiliated with the financial departments.
</P>
<P>
The ministry also said it plans to offer the bonds at other
commercial banks and some urban cooperative banks.
</P>
<P>
With the new issue, the offering of the earlier batch of
three-year certificate bonds will not end until December 31,
rather than October 20 as was previously scheduled.
</P>
<P>
China has issued two groups of bonds this year. Between January
22 and February 17, it issued 20 billion yuan of two-year
government bonds.
</P>
<P>
China's treasury bond issue has been growing rapidly in recent
years, to reach more than 195 billion yuan last year. This year's
treasury bond issue is expected to reach more than 250 billion
yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
