<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Economic Progress Becomes Focus of World Attention (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 21 (Xinhua) -- China's economy has gone through
an important period of both opportunities and challenges since the
14th National Congress of the Communist Party of China (CPC) held
in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The Xinhua News Agency and the People's Daily pointed today to
the remarkable economic achievements China has scored since the
14th CPC National Congress held five years ago, saying that the
country has attained its goal of sustained, speedy, and healthy
economic growth as local governments have carried out the central
policy of accelerating the development of a socialist market
economy.
</P>
<P>
It quoted economists as saying that the country's current
macro-economic situation is very sound, with high growth and low
inflation, and that it has a sound foundation for achieving its
long-term goals.
</P>
<P>
China has adopted a series of measures to reinforce and improve
its macro-economic controls that have gradually alleviated or
eliminated some obstacles to economic progress.
</P>
<P>
In those five years China had a "soft-landing" with an annual
growth of 11.6 percent and a noticeable decline in the inflation
rate, from 25.2 percent in October 1992 to 1.8 percent in the
first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
It has reached its goal of quadrupling 1980's GDP by the year
2000 five years ahead of schedule. And while strengthening
macro-economic controls, the central government has placed greater
emphasis on economic growth tied to the market and to developing
agriculture, infrastructure, and basic industries.
</P>
<P>
In the past five years, the Chinese government has had a
moderately tight monetary policy, successfully bringing down the
amount of currency in circulation from 152.7 billion yuan in 1993
to 91.7 billion yuan in 1996, while the growth of capital
investment in the country has dropped from 58.6 percent in 1992 to
18.2 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, both the central and local governments have during
that period increased investment in agriculture and have
encouraged farmers engaged in grain production with a reasonable
pricing policy that has, in turn, helped curb inflation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970821.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Economic Progress Becomes Focus of World Attention (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The market has played a bigger role in China's economy, and the
price of goods, which used to be set by the state, are now mostly
decided by supply and demand.
</P>
<P>
Every kind of market from the stock market to the labor market
has emerged in that time and they are gradually being
standardized. Laws governing market activities have been passed,
forming a legal system for socialist market economy.
</P>
<P>
A series of reforms have helped improve macro-economic
controls, such as the separation of central and local revenues and
taxation, the issuing of state bonds instead of the government's
overdrawing from banks to cover deficits, and the convertibility
of Chinese currency under current accounts.
</P>
<P>
The reforms have led to co-ordination and co-operation between
planning, banking, and financial sectors, and a multi-layered
situation has appeared since the 14th CPC National Congress. Open
areas have moved from coastal regions to inland provinces, and
more industries, including trade and banking sectors, have been
opened up to foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
In the past five years, the country has made effective use of
both domestic and international markets, and resources and
funds. In 1996, imports and exports totaled 289.9 billion US
dollars, a 124.4-billion-US-dollar increase over 1992, with a
yearly growth of 15 percent, and in the same year, it had 42.35
billion US dollars in foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of this year, the country's foreign exchange
reserves reached 126 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The standard of living has improved in the five years, along
with social development and social stability. From 1992 to 1996,
per-capita income rose from 1,826 yuan to 4,400 yuan for urban
residents and from 784 yuan to 1,900 yuan for rural people. And,
the nation's poverty-elimination program that began in 1993 has
helped more than 22 million people to get out of poverty.
</P>
<P>
In those five years, China has added over seven million jobs,
and has added re-employment programs nationwide to help the
jobless and those who have been laid off. In the first half of
this year, some five million people joined job training programs
and 2.45 million unemployed have been given jobs. A minimum-wage
system has also been adopted in 156 major cities to ensure a
certain level of life for even the lowest-income families. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
