<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over 100 Rebels killed, 300 Injured In Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Over 100 Tamil rebels were
killed and 300 others injured in a fierce fighting Wednesday with
government troops, who continued attack on Puliyankulam town in
the Northern Province of Sri Lanka, according to a military
spokesman her today.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said large groups of rebels confronted the
government troops at four locations in general area east and west
of Puliyankulam town. Troops engaged rebel strong points
effectively causing heavy casualties among the rebels.
</P>
<P>
He said rebels continued to fire mortars at the advancing
troops. The artillery carried out effective counter bombardment
missions at suspected rebel mortar positions. Armor provided
effective fire support to infantry to overcome enemy resistance.
</P>
<P>
By early afternoon troops were in complete control of the four
locations where the fighting took place. Troops also captured 3
trench lines occupied by rebels, who were forced to vacate and
flee further northward with their casualties.
</P>
<P>
He said fighting on Wednesday was intense and hence, casualties
in rebel side reported by Tamil rebel radio totaled 90, including
5 women cadres killed.
</P>
<P>
So far, one officer and 5 soldiers were killed in action and 4
officers and 46 soldiers wounded as a result of fighting on
Wednesday, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Troops at present are 500 Meters South of the Puliyankulam
Railway Station and are in the process of consolidation in the
newly captured areas. Foot patrols continue to dominate areas
ahead of defenses.
</P>
<P>
The troops launched the campaign on the town in an effort to
recapture the highway that links the government-held Vavuniya to
Kilinochchi further north, a vital supply route to the North Jaffn
Peninsula.  
</P>
</TEXT>
