<HEADLINE> Over 100 Rebels Surrender in Northwest Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- About 125 rebels have
surrendered in northwestern Uganda in the last two weeks, "The
New Vision" reported today.
</P>
<P>
Nathan Katagara, Commander of 409 brigade, told the paper that
rebels of Uganda National Rescue Front Part Two (UNRF II) in
Aringa county of Aura district, found no room for them to hide
because local residents often reported their trace to the authorities.
</P>
<P>
Uganda army had launched two battles in Aringa recently,
killing 39 rebels, and capturing 109 rifles. The remnants divided
themselves into tiny groups.
</P>
<P>
Early this week, officials in Arua district told a meeting
chaired by Francis Ayume, Minister of Lands, Housing and Urban
Development, that most of the 240 West Nile Bank Front (WNBF)
rebels freed by the government have joined UNRF II later.
</P>
<P>
Local leaders suggested that some arrangement be made for the
freed rebels including creating jobs for them.
</P>
<P>
WNBF is a crippled rebel group acting in the north-west, whose
main forces have been eliminated in March this year.  
</P>
