<HEADLINE> Mbeki Warns of Corruption Crisis in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 21 (Xinhua) -- South African Deputy
President Thabo Mbeki has warned his countrymen not to
under-estimate the dangers of deep-rooted corruption in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Many people do not understand the depth of the crisis, Mbeki
told parliament in Cape Town on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He said South Africa needs to discuss the crisis at greater
length to let people to have a better understanding of the
problem.
</P>
<P>
He was asked to comment on a recent report by the German-based
non-governmental organisation, Transparency International, in
which South Africa ranked 33rd out of 52 countries in a clean
government poll.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki demanded caution in interpreting the findings of the
poll, saying it did not imply that one country was more corrupt
than another.
</P>
<P>
In a separate nation-wide poll released Wednesday, more than
70 percent of the people asked said they believed there was
corruption among state employees.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki said the first step was to recognise that the democratic
South Africa had inherited a corrupt society.
</P>
<P>
In another development, the National Party spokesman Theo
Alant said Wednesday that the government should make the war
against corruption a national priority.
</P>
<P>
African Christian Democratic Party leader Kenneth Meshoe said
it was correct to put the blame on the government, which was "too
soft on corruption", just as it was too soft on crime. 
</P>
</TEXT>
