<HEADLINE> ADB Expands Water Supply in Thailand's Poorest Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB)
today approved a 50 million U.S. dollar loan to Thailand to help
expand water supply in the country's poorest region.
</P>
<P>
Safe drinking water will be provided to 350,000 people in
Thailand's two northeastern provinces of Nong Khai and Udon Thani
with the help of the loan, the ADB said in a news release.
</P>
<P>
The ADB loan will represent 58 percent of the total cost of the
Nong Khai-Udon Thani Water Supply project, which will help the
provincial waterworks authority provide better water services.
</P>
<P>
The loan has a repayment period of 25 years, including a grace
period of 5 years, at an interest determined in accordance with
the Bank's variable lending rate system for U.S. dollar loans,
currently 6.82 percent.  
</P>
