<HEADLINE> Building Industry Growing in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 21 (Xinhua) -- China's building industry has
had average annual growth of 30.6 percent over the past five
years, coming in fourth as a contributor to the country's GDP,
after agriculture, industry and commerce.
</P>
<P>
The sector had 828.22 billion yuan in output last year, about
half of which came from state enterprises, nearly three times that
of 1992, according to a recent State Statistics Bureau (SSB)
report.
</P>
<P>
A total of 600 million sq.m. of building was completed last
year, including 320 million sq.m. of residential space, providing
housing for some seven million urban families.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1996, the building industry had more than 41,300
businesses with over 21 million workers, with state and collective
businesses still the overwhelming majority.
</P>
<P>
Private enterprises began to edge in last year, with 535
businesses and more than 80,000 employees. Overseas-backed
businesses added 805 with some 170,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
The building sector also tried its luck abroad. It now does
business with 180 countries and regions. Last year, it had more
than 24,000 contracts worth 10 billion US dollars, up 56 percent
from 1992, and did two and half times the amount of business of
1992.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai Baoshan Iron and Steel Corporation, the Guangdong
Daya Nuclear Power Plant, and the Beijing-Kowloon Railway tested
the industry's design and construction capability, a reversal of
the past when China's building industry was not able to handle
major, sophisticated projects.
</P>
<P>
Market competition has been introduced into the sector to
improve project quality and efficiency, and as a result, there is
more fair play in public bidding.
</P>
<P>
The increasing reforms have also helped productivity in the
industry, which last year was 2.6 times that of 1992, with an
annual average rise of 26.8 percent, the SSB reports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
