<HEADLINE> Pakistan Regrets over Indian Statements on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan expressed here today
its regrets over statements recently made by Indian officials who
insisted "Jammu Kashmir is an integral part of India and Kashmir
is non-negotiable".
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a weekly news conference here, a Foreign Office
spokesman said, "these statements are regrettably, entirely
untenable in terms law, justice, historical commitments and
specially in view of the clear agreement reached between India and
Pakistan in June 1997 placing Jammu and Kashmir on the Agenda of
the Foreign Secretary level talks between the two countries."
</P>
<P>
"Jammu and Kashmir is universally recognized as a disputed
territory, the future of which is to be decided through a fair and
impartial plebiscite conducted under the UN auspices," the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He said that Pakistan and India are currently conducting a
dialogue at the level of Foreign Secretaries in order to address
all outstanding issues between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
"The agreed agenda includes, among others, the issues of Jammu
and Kashmir and peace and security in the region which would be
addressed through the integrated mechanism established at the
Second Round of Foreign Secretary level talks (in June)," he said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman reiterated that "Pakistan is looking forward to
comprehensive and meaningful discussions on all outstanding issues
with India".
</P>
<P>
"We sincerely hope that India, during the talks, would
reciprocate the sincerity of purpose with which Pakistan initiated
the resumption of dialogue with India," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
