<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Anti-Smoking Conference To Open in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 21 (Xinhua) -- An international anti-smoking
conference is scheduled for August 24-28 in the Chinese capital,
home to 320 million smokers and a giant tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
The 10th World Conference on Tobacco or Health will not only be
an important forum for the world's anti-smoking organizations, but
will also provide much-needed backup for China's decade-long
smoking-control efforts, according to one of the organizers.
</P>
<P>
"It is very meaningful that, for the first time, a developing
country is hosting such a conference," said Han Changlin, deputy
secretary-general of the organizing committee.
</P>
<P>
"Even more important is that China's anti-smoking forces will
learn a lot from their overseas counterparts and get help with
their campaigns," he added.
</P>
<P>
The conference, themed "Tobacco: The Growing Epidemic," has
attracted about 2,000 delegates from China and 103 other countries
and regions. That number will increase in the next several days,
Han said.
</P>
<P>
He said the five-day conference has the support of the Chinese
government. President Jiang Zemin was invited to be an honorary
member of the conference. Wu Jieping, vice-chairman of the
National People's Congress Standing Committee, China's top
legislator, will serve as president.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will focus on the tobacco industry's expansion into
developing countries, smoking control, new methods to help quit
smoking, passive smoking, as well as tobacco's effects on women
and young people.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of symposiums and discussions, as well as an exhibition,
will be held at the Beijing International Conference Center.
</P>
<P>
Last year, China's cigarette output reached a record 1.7
trillion, while the proportion of smokers among the people older
than 15 increased to a new high of 37.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
"China will have two million people who die from
smoking-related illnesses annually by the year 2025, if preventive
measures are not taken immediately," China's Minister of Health
Chen Minzhang warned recently.
</P>
<P>
China's smoking-control drive was launched in 1979, mainly
targeting teenagers and students, physicians, teachers, and
government employees.
</P>
<P>
As of July, a total of 72 major cities have banned smoking in
public places. 
</P>
</TEXT>
