<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Development Areas Join Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The economic and technological
development areas, pioneers of China's reform and opening to the
outside world, have their own page on the Internet effective today.
</P>
<P>
The "Window for Development Areas in China" page will offer
Chinese and foreign investors information concerning China's
investment environment, policies and other pertinent information.
</P>
<P>
The State Council's Office for Special Economic Zones and the
China Information Association issued an April announcement on
plans to create the page. "Window for Development Areas in China"
(Internet address: http://www.sezo.gov.cn) will be offered through
the China Economic Information Net (CeiNet) which is linked to
Internet.
</P>
<P>
The page will offer information on a selected group of highly
efficient and rapidly developing areas with favorable investment
environments.
</P>
<P>
The 48 areas appearing on the page will include 32 state-level
and 12 provincial-level development areas. The page currently
offers information in both Chinese and English, with plans calling
for the addition of Japanese in the near future. All information
will be updated on a regular basis.
</P>
<P>
The State Council approved the first group of economic and
technological development areas in selected coastal cities at the
end of 1984, and 11 years ago today Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping
wrote "Development areas are full of promise."
</P>
<P>
Development areas have not only recorded the nation's most
rapid development over the past 13 years, but have also attracted
the largest volume of overseas investment.
</P>
<P>
China's development areas attracted overseas investments
totalling 13.2 billion US dollars between 1992-1996.
</P>
<P>
The development areas are facing new challenges resulting from
reduced state preferential policies, and are now expected to take
advantage of favorable structures created since their
establishment.
</P>
<P>
The new Internet page is expected to provide a favorable
investment environment needed for the further development of these
areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
