<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetan Studies Attract More Chinese Scholars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 21 (Xinhua) -- An ever increasing number of
Chinese scholars have been attracted to Tibetan studies, which
enjoy support from the central government.
</P>
<P>
More than 2,000 researchers from over 50 institutions are
currently engaged in Tibetan studies, a discipline involving
research related to the society and culture of the Tibetan ethnic
group which inhabits the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau, an area known as
the "roof of the world."
</P>
<P>
Tibetan studies also cover the ethnic group's written and
spoken language, and other human studies areas such as history,
philosophy, religion, literature, arts and folklore; social
sciences areas such as politics and economics; and Tibetan
medicine, astronomy, geography, architecture and natural sciences.
</P>
<P>
Tibetan studies have also attracted a number scholars from
countries in Europe, Asia, the Americas and Oceania.
</P>
<P>
Over the past few decades, the central government has
encouraged research of Tibetan culture, and has allocated
substantial funding to establish research institutions and train
personnel.
</P>
<P>
The Bibliography on Tibetan Studies in China lists 1,497 types
of books published in China between 1949-1992. According to recent
estimates, nearly 1,000 kinds of books on Tibetan studies have
been published over the past five years.
</P>
<P>
Chinese scholars have played an active role in expanding
academic exchanges with their counterparts abroad and have
translated many important works by foreign specialists.
</P>
<P>
The ongoing 1997 Beijing Seminar on Tibetan Studies follows
international seminars on Tibetan studies held in Beijing and
Lhasa in 1986 and 1991 respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970821.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong's Re-export Slightly Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The re-export accounted for 86
 percent of the value of Hong Kong's total export in the first
half of this year, compared with 85 percent recorded in the same
period of last year, official figures showed today.
</P>
<P>
According to the statistics released by the Census and
Statistics Department of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region's government, the re-export also accounted for 40 percent
of Hong Kong's total value of external trade in the first six
months of 1997, the same as the year-ago level.
</P>
<P>
China's inland areas remained the largest partner for Hong
Kong's re-export trade. As a source, re-export originating in
China's inland areas accounted for 57 percent of Hong Kong's
re-export value during January-June, while as a destination, the
inland areas' share was 36 percent, according to the figures.
</P>
<P>
Much of the re-export trade involving China's inland areas is
related to outward processing, as raw materials and
semi-manufactured goods are exported to these areas for processing
 while the final products are subsequently returned to Hong Kong
and re-exported to overseas markets, the statistics showed.
</P>
<P>
Other main re-export partners of Hong Kong in the first half of
 the year included the United States, Japan, Taiwan, South Korea,
Germany and Britain.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
