<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Achieves Results in Population Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The increasing investment in
population control has sharply cut the average number of children
per woman in Vietnam, the Vietnam News Agency quoted a recent
study as saying.
</P>
<P>
The study, conducted by a group of Vietnamese experts with
overseas technical assistance, shows that the Vietnamese
government has increased funds for family planning activities from
47 billion Vietnamese Dong in 1979 to 262 billion Vietnamese Dong
this year.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the average number of children per woman in
Vietnam has dropped from 4.6 in 1979 to 2.69 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The study concludes that "for every Vietnamese Dong spent on
population and family planning at the national level, the
government will save 7.6 Vietnamese dong in other social services
by 2010."
</P>
<P>
Vietnam has been striving to reduce the population growth rate
to 1.5-1.6 percent, with an aim to keep the population at 81
million by 2000 and to attain the goal of putting the two-child
family model in place by 2005.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the population of Vietnam stood at 76 million with a
growth rate of 1.88 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
