<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing's Ground Water Levels Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Ground water levels in China's
capital have picked up for the first time in 40 years after a
"recharging underground river water" project.
</P>
<P>
The large-scale project began in September of 1995 and has
brought water levels in the western and southern parts of Beijing
along the Yongding River up more than four meters.
</P>
<P>
Water conservation departments use movable rubber dams or river
gates to raise water levels in some rivers.
</P>
<P>
More than 600 million cu.m. of surface water has gone
underground along the Yongding and Chaobai rivers.
</P>
<P>
Beijing has a population of more than 12 million, but per
capita water resources were only 400 square meters, a 25th of the
world's average.
</P>
<P>
Experts here predict that, over the next 20 years, Beijing's
water supplies are expected to go down as per capita consumption
doubles.
</P>
<P>
Beijing has seen three water crises since the founding of new
China in 1949, and the excessive extraction of ground water has
caused the water table to drop from two meters deep in the 1950s
to some 15 meters in many areas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970821.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aftermath Of East China Typhoon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, August 21 (Xinhua)-- People in parts of Zhejiang
province who were hit by flooding for three days because of
typhoon Winnie were evacuated to safer ground, and they have
started rebuilding their homes.
</P>
<P>
People in the city of Taizhou began repairing a 300-kilometer
sea wall yesterday morning. The same is true for five sea walls in
Wenling City, where the typhoon slammed into Zhejiang.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government has asked local governments to help
the hardest hit, and to resume industrial and agricultural
production in disaster areas as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Niu Maosheng, minister of water resources, visited Taizhou,
which was the hardest hit, to talk to local people yesterday. The
Zhejiang Military Region has also sent troops to help the people
of Sanmen, Ninghai and Luqiao.
</P>
<P>
Meteorologists say the typhoon was the most violent to hit
China in a decade. It flooded 10.97 million mu (730,000 hectares)
of farmland and 24 cities and towns in Zhejiang and resulted in
direct losses of 20 billion yuan (about 2.5 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
In spite of the heavy losses, local departments are trying to
provide enough rice and non-staple foods to typhoon-hit areas, and
health departments have sent medical teams and medicines.
</P>
<P>
Officials say most power and communications had been restored,
and the airports in Hangzhou, Wenzhou, Ningbo and Luqiao were
operating yesterday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
