<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Up Slightly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar finished
stronger against the U.S. dollar today despite falling prey to
profit-taking which knocked it back off its intraday highs.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar traded between 74.43 and 74.69 U.S. cents
before closing at 74.44.
</P>
<P>
Overnight players bought in the currency in New York as
sentiment grew that the Reserve Bank of Australia will not cut
interest rates again in the near term, IBJ's senior foreign
exchange manager Shane Spurway said.
</P>
<P>
"There may still be one more rate cut at the end of the year,
it is just a matter of waiting for the data to come through," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Traders said the local session was quiet with prices trading in
a narrow range for much of the day, but the short end managed to
lift up off its intraday price lows toward the close.
</P>
<P>
On the cross-rates, the Australian dollar was at 87.79 from
87.74 against the Japanese yen, and was at 1.3814 from 1.3712
against the German mark.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
