<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Predicts Higher Growth Rate for South Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Despite successive bankruptcies of
the country's conglomerates, including the Kia Group, the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) has forecast a high economic
growth rate of 6.5 percent for South Korea this year.
</P>
<P>
The GDP-based IMF figure, released today, is much higher than
the 5.7 percent the international economic body predicted in May.
</P>
<P>
The IMF said that a series of insolvencies of conglomerates
such as Hanbo and Kia would not seriously affect the nation's
total production and exports capability.
</P>
<P>
On the contrary, South Korea's exports and investment would
revive and thus raise the economic growth rate, the IMF added.
</P>
<P>
The IMF also estimated a stable 4.5 percent in consumer prices
and 20 billion U.S. dollars in current account deficit this year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Bank of Korea said Wednesday that the nation's
GDP growth rate reached 5.9 percent in the first half this year,
predicting that the nation's GDP growth rate would reach about 7
percent, far exceeding its earlier forecast of 6 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
