<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Coastal Areas Experimenting With State Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 21 (Xinhua) -- China's coastal areas have been
experimenting with state-owned capital reforms by bringing them in
line with the market, "People's Daily" reports here today.
</P>
<P>
The reforms cover the fields of acquisitions, reorganization,
coalitions, stock transfers, and selling shares on the domestic or
overseas markets.
</P>
<P>
State-owned property and assets used to be fixed for a long
time under the planned economy, with available assets not being
very efficient, resulting in large losses to the state.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen City in south China's Guangdong Province, which has
been a front runner in reforms, reported net state-owned assets of
26.6 billion yuan in 1996, a rise of 16 billion yuan from 1992.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai, at the eastern end of the Yangtze River economic
belt, has helped stronger state-owned enterprises with better
capital operations.
</P>
<P>
In east China's Jiangsu Province, officials decided that 1997
was the year for adjusting the industrial structure, and capital
operations are an important means of doing this.
</P>
<P>
Zhejiang Province, Jiangsu's neighbor, also developed a program
this year to help breathe life into 10 billion yuan worth of
assets through acquisitions, bankruptcies, and auctions, and to
raise 12 billion yuan through the stock market.
</P>
<P>
More than 400 large enterprises in Shanghai now have brighter
prospects because of transferred business rights.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin Municipality in north China has increased efforts to
attract more overseas funds, and last year used 3.9 billion
U.S. dollars worth of overseas investment, putting it second in
China in use of such funds.
</P>
<P>
Coastal areas have done some valuable experimental work in
establishing better management of state-owned assets by separating
authority, management, and supervision. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
