<HEADLINE> Kenya Assured of British Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's expected aid from
Britain worth some 3.4 billion Shillings (about 56 million U.S.
Dollars) for 1998 will not be affected by the International
Monetary Fund (IMF)'s key loan suspension, British High
Commissioner Jeffrey James has said.
</P>
<P>
British High Commissioner to Kenya, Jeffrey James, assured
that Britain will continue its bilateral aid programs for Kenya,
noting these programs are largely geared towards poverty
alleviation, according to local press reports today.
</P>
<P>
"While the IMF has got its own criteria for giving or cutting
aid, the long-standing bilateral relations between Kenya and
Britain will not be jeopardized by the IMF's decision," James was
quoted as saying on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He also urged donor agencies and countries to channel more aid
through the private sector in Kenya to enhance their capacity and
make them pro-active.
</P>
<P>
Despite recent violence which seemed to have created some fear
about the suitability of Kenya as a good investment place, the
country's business climate remains very resilient, James added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the British commissioner lauded the Kenyan
government for promoting and supporting small-scale sized
enterprises, saying it fostered the country's economic
development, especially in private sectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
