<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bosnian Serb Government Accuses UN and Alliance-led Forces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The Bosnian Serb government
issued a statement here today accusing the Multinational
Stablization Force (SFOR) and the International Police Task Force
(IPTF) for their forcible occupation of the police headquarters in
Banja Luka.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this morning, the SFOR and IPTF occupied with force the
building of the police headquarters and the three police stations
in the city of Banja Luka. They did so in the name of the Interior
Ministry of the Serb Republic, the Yugoslavia Tanjug news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Three-hundred-and-fifty British and Czech soldiers, 50 armored
vehicles and several helicopters participated in the action.
</P>
<P>
The action took place following Bosnian Serb President Biljana
Plavsic's meeting with the International High Representative to
Bosnia, Carlos Westendorp, and the United States envoy, Robert
Gelbard.
</P>
<P>
Reports said the SFOR and IPTF launched the action on the
requirement of Plavsic.
</P>
<P>
It could possibly lead to the split of the Serb Republic into
two powers, said Momcilo Krajisnik, member of the Presidency of
Bosnia. He thought that this anti-constitutional act of Plavsic's
might result in an anarchic state for the nation.
</P>
<P>
Plavsic got into serious disputes over important issues
with the parliament of the Serb Republic and the government in
early July.
</P>
<P>
She declared parliament dissolved on July 3. On July 7,
the government challenged her in the constitutional court, which
declared, on August 15, the president's decision unconstitutional
and, therefore, invalid.
</P>
<P>
With the conflicts of the two disputed sides turning white-hot,
the U.S.-led Western countries overtly indicated their support for
Plavsic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
