<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- President Jacques Chirac Wednesday took advantage of the first
government cabinet session after the summer vacation to climb to the
crenel: He expressed deep reserves over the government's draft law
on employment for the youth, which calls for the creation of 350,000
jobs by the state.
</P>
<P>
-- The 300,000 Tziganes in the Czech Republic, subjected to
violence and racism after the fall of the Berlin Wall, are seeking
to emigrate to Canada to start a new life. Seventy percent of the
Tziganes in the country are jobless, and some regions in northern
Bohemia and Moravia have turned into real ghettos and pockets of
misery ignored by the government.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- Three weeks after the last bombing attack by Hamas in
Jerusalem, Yasser Arafat rallied on Wednesday with the Palestinian
Islamic movements at a ``conference of national unity'' during which
Islamic militants called for armed actions against Israel, while
Arafat called for the adoption of a unified position by Palestinians
``to face up to the challenges of this dangerous period.''
</P>
<P>
-- The number of tax-payers for family wealth tax -- the ISF --
in France has dropped to 174,726 in 1996, 1,200 fewer than 1995, and
the ISF income last year amounted to 8.92 billion francs (1.78
billion U.S. dollars), less than the 9.07 billion francs (1.81
billion U.S. dollars) expected by the government, according to the
Ministry of Economy and Finance. One of the reasons behind this
could be the transfer of properties by wealthy French families to
foreign countries. 
</P>
