<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from the Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- The Turkish Cabinet has approved a transportation
agreement with Russia in an effort to promote cooperation between
the two countries in this field.
</P>
<P>
The decision was published on the Wednesday edition of the
Official Gazette, according to the semi-official Anatolia News
Agency.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the two countries will cooperate closely
on transportation regulations, facilities and other aspects.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by representatives of the two sides in
the Russian port city of Novorossiysk on June 18 when the fourth
meeting of the Turco-Russian Joint Transportation Committee was
held.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Government offices in Abu Dhabi Emirate of the
United Arab Emirates (UAE) have been urged to cut spending for
1998 to trim a persistent budget deficit, the UAE's Wam news
agency said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Abu Dhabi finance department has sent letters to the local
ministries in the wealthy emirate to ask them to submit their
draft budgets before September 25, Wam said.
</P>
<P>
"All departments are urged to make significant reductions in
their expenditure for 1998," said the letter published by Wam.
</P>
<P>
"Spending should be evaluated according to real needs of
each department, taking into consideration lower spending for
unnecessary requirements," the letter said.
</P>
<P>
Despite a surge in oil earnings in 1996, the deficit in
the UAE's overall budget was as high as some 4.8 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
TUNIS -- Tunisia has so far exported 20,745 tonnes of olive oil
during the current season to the European Union (EU) countries,
and exports will continue boosting as the season of olive harvest
in Tunisia lasts from April till October.
</P>
<P>
According to a Tunisian news agency report Wednesday, the olive
department at the Tunisian ministry of commerce has exported
13,164 tonnes of olive oil, while the private sector's exports
reached 7,581 tonnes.
</P>
<P>
During the past season of olive oil exporting, the olive oil
exports did not exceed 5,050 tonnes.
</P>
<P>
Tunisia ranks second among the olive oil exporting countries
after Spain. Most Tunisian exports are directed to the EU states
which will import 45,000 tonnes of Tunisia's olive oil this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
