<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Get Tough with Fish Poachers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 21 (Xinhua) -- South African cabinet
ministers Wednesday approved plans to get tough on fishing
vessels poaching in remote waters near Antarctica.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the presidential office today said the
cabinet meeting studied a report stating that poaching within
South Africa's economic zone around the Prince Edward Islands is
likely to cut fish numbers severely.
</P>
<P>
"The cabinet approved a joint operation plan to enforce the
exclusive economic zone," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Ministry of Environmental Affairs said the
plan is for the navy and air force to begin air and surface
patrols around Prince Edward Islands as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
The presence of Patagonian toothfish off the Prince Edward
Islands, whose flesh sells for around seven U.S. Dollars a
kilogram, was discovered only about 18 months ago.
</P>
<P>
Long-line fishing boats have since flocked to the area, having
decimated populations of the fish off South America where it was
first exploited, according to local media reports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
