<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Plans to Build Farm Workers' Houses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Agriculture Labour
Bureau (ALB) is seeking 1.5 billion Zimbabwe Dollars (140 million
U.S. Dollars) to construct about 18,000 housing units for over
370,000 farm workers around the country, the "Herald" daily
newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
ALB Chief Executive Ewen Rodger told the paper that the funds
will be used under the bureau's 10-year plan.
</P>
<P>
The bureau wants to construct suitable housing units for all
permanent employees in about 4,000 commercial farms in the
country under the agricultural workers welfare plan.
</P>
<P>
According to Roger, proposed housing units for a household are
a minimum of three-roomed accommodation of permanent structure, a
durable roof and adequate ventilation with a separate kitchen.
</P>
<P>
Under the agricultural workers welfare plan, Roger noted, ALB
wants to ensure access to education for children of farm workers
up to and including grade seven level at a registered school
within 10 km of their homes or through distance education.
</P>
</TEXT>
