<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-21 07:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Expands Cuts in Customs Duties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Egypt has ordered reduction of
import duties on certain goods, the second in a month, as part of
its program to liberalize trade.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to reduce the prices and improve the standard of
living of the Egyptian people, President Hosni Mubarak Wednesday
issued a decree to change the state's tariffs and customs
regulations to provide further customs reductions, the Egyptian
Gazette reported today.
</P>
<P>
The customs reduction covered medicine, baby milk formula,
computer sets, software and programs, printing paper, certain
sorts of ready-made clothes, gold items, and raw materials.
</P>
<P>
"This decision is one of a series of customs reduction measures
started in September 1996," said Finance Minister Mohi Eddin
el-Gharieb.
</P>
<P>
The government is working to further reduce customs on the long
run to cope with the ongoing Egyptian trade liberalization
measures, he said.
</P>
<P>
On July 12, the Egyptian government ordered tariffs cut by five
percentage points for most consumer goods, such as televisions,
washing machines, gas oven, refrigerators and other home
appliances, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The reductions are part of an economic liberalization program
approved with the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and came in
the wake of an IMF executive board meeting in Washington on July
16 that reviewed an internal second quarterly report on the
Egyptian government's economic performance.
</P>
<P>
But the decision did not mean that the government would lift
its protection for national industry, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
Rather, "the reductions take into consideration the national
industry by providing an acceptable and suitable amount of
protection," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
