<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Papua New Guinea Has High Incidence of HIV </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Papua New Guinea (PNG) was on
the verge of an AIDS epidemic that could be as serious as in some
African countries such as Uganda with young women the main risk
group, PNG health authorities and the WHO representative here
warned today.
</P>
<P>
PNG now has the third highest per capita incidence of HIV
infection in the Pacific Rim region, the country's Health Minister
Ludger Mond said today while announcing plans to develop a
national HIV/AIDS strategy.
</P>
<P>
There are 745 reported cases of HIV (Human Immunodeficiency
Virus), the virus that causes AIDS, in PNG. However, Mond said
this was only likely to be the "tip of the iceberg" with the real
figure estimated at 10,000, the Australian Associated Press
reported.
</P>
<P>
PNG's population stood at 4.074 million in 1995, according to
official estimates.
</P>
<P>
Of the reported cases, 629 are in the Port Moresby district
where better health services allow for the detection of the virus.
</P>
<P>
The World Health Organization's PNG Representative Dr. Paul
Chen said that immediate action through education programs was
needed to arrest the epidemic.
</P>
<P>
"The prevalence here is higher than Australia, higher than
Fiji, higher than New Caledonia and so on," he said.
</P>
<P>
"And from that point of view, and the rapidity of the increase
... it shows that we are right in the midst of an epidemic.
</P>
<P>
"And if we don't do something fast we could end up like
Uganda... you would have seen the villages abandoned, people are
dying, a whole generation missing," he warned.
</P>
<P>
The highest HIV infection rate is among women aged 17 to 35,
according to Health Department statistics.
</P>
<P>
Sixty-five percent of those under 26 with the infection were
women, according to the department's Deputy Secretary, Timothy
Pyakalyia.
</P>
<P>
Pyakalyia blamed the high rate of infection of young women on
the social disadvantages they face in PNG and their exploitation
by older men who were carrying the virus.
</P>
<P>
"In developing countries younger females are basically being
exploited by older males who are financially secure," he said.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Chen said that an education program was the main priority
of the strategy as he released an AIDS/HIV booklet which also
takes into account cultural aspects peculiar to PNG.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
