<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Ruling ANC Is Losing Support : Shows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Public discontent with
South Africa's ruling African National Congress (ANC) is growing,
according to a survey released Wednesday by the Human Science
Research Council.
</P>
<P>
The survey conducted in February this year shows that 73
percent of all South Africans suspect the civil sevice is
corrupt, while 64 pecent think the government headed by President
Nelson Mandela is wasting taxpayers' money, local daily Sowetan
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Only one third of those questioned were satisfied with the
country's economic situation.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, a total of 2,197 South Africans above
the age of 18 were polled in February.
</P>
<P>
The survey shows that although the ANC government is losing
support, Mandela is enjoying more popularity. Sixty-one percent
feel Mandela is doing a good job, compared to 60 percent as
showed in a survey in February last year.
</P>
<P>
But satisfaction with the way in which the country was being
governed had dropped from 53 to 43 percent over the period.
</P>
<P>
Satisfaction with provincial governments had also taken a
negative turn, with only four of the country's nine provinces
receiving a nod of approval from more than 50 percent from their
voters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
