<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over Half of Ugandan Population Infected with TB </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- About to 50 to 70 percent of
Ugandans are infected with tuberculosis disease, reported the
local daily "The Monitor" today.
</P>
<P>
Peter Bukenya, Uganda's Mukono district leprosy and
tubercykisis control supervisor, was quoted as saying that TB is
a chronic and infectious disease caused by a mycrobacterum
tuberculosis. About 10 percent of them develop the disease.
</P>
<P>
He made the statement Tuesday at a TB control seminar held
in Mukono, about 30 km east of Kampala, the capital.
</P>
<P>
This percentage may be multiplied by 2 to 4 due to HIV
infection, because 66 out of every 1000 TB cases are HIV
positive.
</P>
<P>
Eight million people world-wide aged between 15 and 54 years
develop TB every year, and 2 to 3 million people die of
the disease annually, Bukenya noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
