<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia's Health Officials Equipped with Computers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's Central Board of Health
has adopted a computer-based tool to enable district health
officials to plan and monitor their activities on a continuous
basis, Zambia Daily Mail reported today.
</P>
<P>
The local newspaper quoted Board Director General John Masange
as saying Wednesday that the officials should acquire the
new skills to enable themselves to carry out tasks they have
never performed before if decentralization has to be successful.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a workshop on new directions in health
communication for the district health officials, Masange said the
workshop will support the process of decentralization by
strengthening district capacity "including planning, using data
for decision making, health communication and education and
community mobilization."
</P>
<P>
He also stressed the necessity to build and strengthen
community partnership, adding that communities are the best way
to reach the population, close to their homes and families.
</P>
<P>
A number of key elements of the health reform process is being
demonstrated at the workshop, which pivots on decentralization,
collaboration and partnership. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
