<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Expand Overseas Education Exchange </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Chinese higher-learning
institutions are encouraged to co-operate with foreign
counterparts in science and technology to boost China's
economy in the 21st century, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
Colleges and universities in China will make more efforts to
train more talented personnel for the country's economic sector,
Zhou Yuan ping, vice-minister of the State Education Commission
(SEC) said during an international symposium on inter-university
cooperation and exchange that opened in Beijing yesterday.
</P>
<P>
The symposium, the first of its kind in China, attracted more
than 200 foreign participants from 100 universities in 17
countries and regions, including the United States, Canada,
Australia, France, Germany, Italy and Japan.
</P>
<P>
In addition to well-known universities in inland areas such as
Beijing and Qinghua universities, officials from the University of
Hong Kong, the Hong Kong Polytechnic University, the Chinese
University of Hong Kong, and Hong Kong Baptist University also
participated.
</P>
<P>
Subjects during the three-day symposium included education
globalization; multilateral and cross-regional exchanges;
co-operation between universities and enterprises; and university
co-operation between eastern and western countries.
</P>
<P>
China has sent an average of 2,000 students abroad each year to
study in 103 countries and regions, and it receives more than
1,000 students each year from 150 countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
The State stepped up the reform of higher learning in the early
1990s, focusing on encouraging both government and non-government
organizations to run schools, restructuring colleges and
universities across the country, and improving curricula and
teaching programs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
