<HEADLINE> Great Lakes Leaders to Discuss Developments in Burundi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 21 (Xinhua) -- A summit of countries in
the Great Lakes region of Africa is expected to open in Tanzania's
northern town of Arusha next week to discuss developments in
Burundi, according to an government official.
</P>
<P>
The local press today quoted the official (no name is
available) as saying on Wednesday that delegates to the meeting
are expected to arrive in Arusha on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Julius Nyerere, former Tanzanian President and facilitator in
the Burundi Peace Talks who will chair the forthcoming summit,
recently expressed his support to the continuation of economic
sanctions against Burundi, saying the regime of Major Pierre
Buyoya has not yet satisfied conditions for lifting the embargo.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere made his remarks in Kinshasa during his recent trip to
the Democratic Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
He said that he supports the decision by the Great Lakes
foreign ministers' meeting in Kampala, Uganda earlier this week
to maintain the embargo on Burundi until the Buyoya regime makes
substantial progress for restoration of democratic rule.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions were imposed in July last year to protest
Buyoya's overthrow of the elected government. The embargo is
observed by Kenya, Ethiopia, Uganda, Zambia, Tanzania, Rwanda,
Zimbabwe and the Democratic Congo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
