<HEADLINE> Iran Welcomes Lift of Iraqi Pilgrim Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Iran's foreign ministry
officially has expressed its welcome to Iraq's unilateral decision
to lift pilgrim travel ban on Iranians, a press report said here
today.
</P>
<P>
The statement was made by Ali Asghar Khaji, foreign ministry
adviser and director general of the Persian Gulf affairs in a
meeting with Iraqi Charge d'affaires Salah al-Samarmad here
Wednesday, the English daily Iran News reported.
</P>
<P>
The daily quoted the Iranian official as saying that the
Iranian administration was pleased at Iraq's lifting of a ban on
Iranian pilgrims visiting holy shrines within Iraq's borders.
</P>
<P>
He said that permission was a positive step toward solving
differences between the two nations, and it could help broaden
ties between Tehran and Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
"Tehran was ready to exchange delegations with Baghdad to work
out details of the pilgrimage," he added.
</P>
<P>
On August 18, Iraq informed Iran of its unilateral decision to
allow Iranians to visit Islam's shrines for the first time since
the 1980-88 war between the two Muslim neighbors.
</P>
<P>
The negotiations on the lifting of the travel ban began in 1990
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The travel ban is to be lifted on September 4, the date on
which Iraq marks the start of their 1980-88 conflict. But Iran says
the war started on September 22 when Baghdad launched an invasion
against Iranian southern provinces.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's unilateral decision to lift travel ban would create a
good atmosphere for the two side to go in for rapprochement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
