<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Expressway to Deng Xiaoping's Hometown Being Built </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Guang'an, Sichuan Province, August 21 (Xinhua) -- When he left
his hometown in a mountainous part of southwestern China for study
in France 79 years ago, 14-year-old Deng Xiaoping rowed a small
wooden boat for four days to get to Chongqing, the nearest major
city, because there was no road.
</P>
<P>
Deng never went back to Paifang Village, Xiexing Town, Guang'an
County, where he was born on August 22, 1904, but now a 110-km
expressway from Guang'an to Chongqing, which is now China's
largest city, is finally being built.
</P>
<P>
"With the completion of the expressway, we won't have to walk
that dusty dirt road or ride that slow-moving boat," says
60-year-old Dan Wenquan, a farmer in Paifang who is one of
Deng's cousins, who is sitting in a farm house with pictures of
Deng Xiaoping on the walls of most of the rooms. "In order to get
to Chongqing, we used to follow dusty trails for eight or nine
days. It was very difficult for us to travel outside."
</P>
<P>
"It was not until 1958 that a dirt road was built between
Guang'an and Chongqing," he notes, "Before then rowing a wooden
boat was our major means of transportation."
</P>
<P>
In recent years, a cement highway was built between Guang'an
and neighbouring counties, so, "We ride the bus or motorcycles
today," Dan says, pointing to the motorcycle in his house.
</P>
<P>
"But it still fell far short to meet the economic development
needs," adds Deng Jian, commissioner of Guang'an Prefecture,
"Transportation is still a handicap for the region's economic
development."
</P>
<P>
Guang'an's industrial output per capita is only one fifth of
China's average and the local people's purchasing power is only a
third of the national average, according to Deng. So Guang'an's
prosperity depends on the highway.
</P>
<P>
It will mean that it takes only an hour to reach Chongqing from
Guang'an on the expressway. Work on the expressway began in 1995
and it is set to open to traffic by the year 2000. It will cost
about one billion yuan (about 83 million US dollars), with the
central government allocating 420 million yuan and the local
governments raising the rest.
</P>
<P>
"Deng Xiaoping is deeply loved by the people in his hometown
and the people throughout China," Deng Jian says, "And the highway
will be the best memorial to him." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970821.0203 </DOCNO>
