<HEADLINE> Peru, Ecuador Win at World Cup South American Qualifiers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Peru and Ecuador both kept
their slim chances for the World Cup finals alive with respective
victories in South American qualifiers on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Ecuador came from behind to shock high-flying Paraguay 2-1 and
Peru hammered hapless Venezuela 3-0.
</P>
<P>
However, Chile, looking to finish third in the nine-team South
American group, went down to Uruguay 1-0.
</P>
<P>
The Chileans succumbed in Montevideo to a first-half goal from
Marcelo Otero of Italy's Vicenza and had Roland Fuentes sent off
on the hour.
</P>
<P>
Uruguay's Paolo Montero also took an early bath near the end,
while teammate and Chelsea star Gustavo Poyet was one of five
players booked in a stormy encounter played before a 38,000 crowd.
</P>
<P>
In a hard-fought clash in Quito, Richard Baez scored after only
five minutes for Paraguay, second in the table behind Argentina
and despite their defeat still set to qualify as one of the best
four sides in the group.
</P>
<P>
Baez fired home in the visitors' first attack after a mistake
by keeper Francisco Cevallos as Paraguay began to entertain
thoughts of going top of the table with the Argentinians not
playing.
</P>
<P>
The goal stunned the 20,000 crowd at the Olimpico Atahualpa
stadium, already furious at the recent home defeat by Colombia and
an embarrassing draw with tailenders Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
But the Ecuadoreans stormed back after the break and Alex
Aguinaga headed the equaliser on 54 minutes from a cross by
impressive substitute Jose Gavica before Ariel Graziani settled
matters with the winner 13 minutes from time.
</P>
<P>
Ecuador, looking to make the final stages of a World Cup for
the first time, now have 18 points from their 14 matches, one less
than Chile and Peru, who both have a match in hand.
</P>
<P>
Peru's triumph in Venezuela, who have yet to win a single game
in 14 attempts, lifted them to fifth in the table behind the
Chileans on goal difference.
</P>
<P>
Manuel Marengo scored the Peruvians' opener on 13 minutes,
naturalised Brazilian Julinho hit the second after 56 minutes and
Flavio Maestri added a third in the closing stages.
</P>
<P>
Colombia were hosting Bolivia in a match which kicked off at
0200 GMT Thursday, looking to leapfrog Paraguay into second place
with three points.
</P>
<P>
Bolivia themselves retain an outside chance of qualifying and a
win in Colombia would put them fourth above Chile, who next host
leaders Argentina. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
