<DOCNO> XIE19970821.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Aims To Improve Environment Quality </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Environmental quality in China's
capital remains stable despite steady growth in the city's economy
and industry, according to a government report.
</P>
<P>
This is the conclusion contained in the report released by the
Beijing Municipal Environmental Protection Bureau yesterday on the
capital city's environmental situation last year, the China Daily
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Measures taken to control industrial pollution at source,
increase the use of clean fuel and reinforce controls on smoke and
dust emissions have resulted in a 36 percent decrease in dust and
dirt in urban and suburban areas compared with 1995.
</P>
<P>
Apart from dirt and dust, other air pollutant indices did not
change very much from those in 1995, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Out of the 78 monitored rivers and 17 monitored reservoirs in
Beijing, 49.9 percent and 48.9 percent respectively have been kept
clean, which is basically unchanged from 1995.
</P>
<P>
Zhao Yixin, director of the Environmental Protection Bureau,
noted that there are still a number of problems related to the
city's environment.
</P>
<P>
He said air pollution in the city generally remains serious,
especially during winter when large amounts of coal and charcoal
are burnt for heating.
</P>
<P>
The rapid increase in the number of automobiles means that
pollution from car exhausts is getting worse on major roads and at
intersections.
</P>
<P>
Some river sections have been polluted by untreated sewage
discharges, and noise is still one of the main nuisances in
people's daily lives.
</P>
<P>
He said Beijing still has much to do to improve its environment
in the future.
</P>
<P>
The Municipal Government has decided that a total of 224
industrial pollution sources under Beijing's jurisdiction should
complete pollution control work by the end of this year, followed
by 138 sources in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The objective set for Beijing is to achieve 60 percent
treatment rates for urban sewage and non-toxic waste by 2000,
according to Zhao. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970821.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Industrial Growth Rate May Fall Below Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The industrial growth of India
is likely to be less than the targeted 12 percent in the fiscal
year of 1997-98 (April-March), the Times of India said today.
</P>
<P>
According to a report by the Punjab-Haryana-Delhi Chamber of
Commerce and Industry, the assessment is based on a slowdown in
demand for manufactured goods, consumer products and capital goods
and the shortages in the infrastructure sector.
</P>
<P>
Industry has been "indifferent" to government policies aimed at
boosting industrial growth owing to the political uncertainty in
the country, the chamber noted.
</P>
<P>
The lack of infrastructural growth is evident in the enlarged
gap between demand and supply in the power sector which has
amounted to 26.9 billion kilowatt-hours, it said.
</P>
<P>
The chamber said in its report that the non-availability of
adequate finances is also a major constraint on the industrial
growth.  
</P>
