<HEADLINE> Thai Researchers Find Anti-AIDS Substance in Liquor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 21 (Xinhua) -- A group of Thai scientists
Wednesday announced the discovery of a substance in liquor waste
which they believe can build an immune system in acquired immuno
deficiency syndrome (AIDS) patients, a local newspaper reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The substance, called gm-glucan which exists in yeast during
the fermenting process of making alcohol and the liquor waste
after distillation or slop, was discovered by researchers from the
Thailand Institute of Scientific and Technological Research, the
Bangkok Post said.
</P>
<P>
The institute is carrying out further testing on the substance
for use as an anti-AIDS cure, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The institute also pointed out that the substance can safeguard
humans from harmful ultraviolet rays and can be widely used to
make beauty cream.  
</P>
</TEXT>
