<DOCNO> XIE19970821.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Thailand Adjusts Investment Policy to Attract     More Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government Wednesday
introduced a new investment plan, apparently relaxing its old
location-concentrated investment policy to attract more investment
and foreign exchange that the country eagerly needs to tide over
its current financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Under the new plan introduced by the Chavalit government,
location will no longer be the determining factor for investment
projects which could enjoy privileges offered by Thailand's Board
of Investment (BOI).
</P>
<P>
The government this time will focus its support on those
projects which could generate foreign exchange, create
considerable job opportunities, produce substitutes for import
goods and have a low import content.
</P>
<P>
Thailand currently is undergoing an ordeal as the country sees
the depreciation of the baht, drop of foreign exchange reserves,
rising unemployment, threat of higher inflation, and the tortured
finance sector.
</P>
<P>
So far, the baht has depreciated by 25 percent after the
government floated the currency on July 2; the country's foreign
reserves have dropped below 33.2 billion U.S. dollars; the number
of employees laid off nationwide reached 7,600 during the first
seven months of this year, exceeding the figure recorded
throughout last year.
</P>
<P>
The financial sector in the country also suffered a torture of
liquidity and the government so far has suspended operations of 58
finance firms of the country's total 91.
</P>
<P>
Thailand now has to turn to the International Monetary Fund and
other governments and international institutions for aid to help
prop up its foreign reserves and bail out its ailing finance
sector.
</P>
<P>
The change in the investment policy is in fact part of the Thai
government's efforts to draw foreign capital inflow to reinforce
the country's foreign reserves.
</P>
<P>
Thailand has been following a policy of encouraging investment
in the provinces since 1972 to build local economies and improve
the living standards of people in the rural areas.
</P>
<P>
In the past, the BOI used a zoning system which divided the
country's 76 provinces (including Bangkok) into three investment
zones.
</P>
<P>
Investment in zone one, which covers Bangkok and its
surrounding provinces of Samut Prakan, Samut Sakhon, Pathum Thani,
Nonthaburi and Nakhon Pathom, received no privileges from the
government.
</P>
<P>
Investment in zone two, which comprised provinces immediately
outside zone one - Samut Songkhram, Ratchaburi, Kanchanaburi,
Suphanburi, Angthong, Ayutthaya, Saraburi, Nakhon Nayok,
Chachoengsao and Chonburi - was granted limited privileges.
</P>
<P>
Investment in zone three which consisted of the remaining
provinces enjoyed support by the government with the full range of
privileges.
</P>
<P>
Yet, the old policy seemed to have some weaknesses as investors
were reluctant to go to the provinces with poor infrastructural
facilities.
</P>
<P>
Thailand had drawn huge sums of foreign investment during the
boom years, but a large part of this foreign capital flew into
non-productive sectors and caused a bubble economy in the country.
</P>
<P>
The foreign capital began to flow out of the country in recent
years as the bubble burst, building up pressure on the country's
currency.
</P>
<P>
BOI Secretary-General Staporn Kavitanond stressed that the
principle of promoting investment in the rural areas still
remained the government's priority and the new policy would be
implemented on a short-term basis.
</P>
<P>
The new policy will be implemented as soon as possible to help
the country to get rid of the current economic grips, he noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970821.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Protests Against Fuel Price Hike in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's nationwide protest
against the price hike of petroleum products continued today amid
violence, rallies and spontaneous strike.
</P>
<P>
The government Monday refixed the prices of all petroleum
products, among which the petrol price rose sharply to 21 taka
(about 0.47 U.S. dollars) from 13.70 taka (about 0.31 dollars), in
a bid to keep pace with the international market.
</P>
<P>
This move, however, triggered sharp reactions among different
political parties and transport circles. The main opposition
Bangladesh Nationalist Party (BNP), which had threatened a
countrywide strike on August 24, launched its four-day agitation
program today.
</P>
<P>
The BNP is scheduled to hold protest rallies and bring out
processions in all counties, district and divisional headquarters
today.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the drivers of autorickshaw (motor tricycle), a
major transport means in Bangladesh, continued their strike today
in the capital Dhaka in protest against the price hike.
</P>
<P>
In southwestern Khulna district, the fuel distributors, truck
owners and workers have called a three-day token strike from
today.
</P>
<P>
In northern Rajshahi, about 1,000 autorickshaw drivers
Wednesday staged a demonstration in front of the city corporation
office. The mayor of Rajshahi city, who joined them, asked the
government to bring down the increased prices of petroleum
products.
</P>
<P>
In the second-largest city Chittagong, the Petroleum Dealers
Association has asked the government to withdraw the increased
price by August 24.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the ruling Awami (people's) League Presidium
at a meeting Wednesday night resolved that price increase of
petroleum products was "inevitable" for keeping it at par with the
price in world market.
</P>
<P>
The meeting noted that the country could no longer bear the
burden of 4.5 billion taka (about 101 million dollars) as revenue
loss in the fuel sector every year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
