<HEADLINE> FBI Investigating Abuse of Missouri Inmates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The Federal Bureau of
Investigation (FBI) said today that it was moving ahead with a
full-scale investigation of the abuse of prisoners.
</P>
<P>
A videotape of the alleged abuse has been broadcast nationwide.
</P>
<P>
Don Clark, the FBI agent in charge, said the agency made the
decision after talking to the district attorney of Brazoria
County, in southeast Texas, and viewing parts of the 30-minute
videotape broadcast Tuesday, news reports said.
</P>
<P>
The tape shows guards kicking inmates in the groin, prodding
them with stun guns and allowing dogs to bite them. It also shows
guards dragging an inmate with a broken ankle by his arm.
</P>
<P>
The tape was reportedly made for training purposes by a
sheriff's deputy on September 18, 1996. One copy was obtained last
week by The Brazosport Facts newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Missouri state officials terminated a six million U.S. dollar
contract to house 415 inmates at the Brazoria County Detention
Center in Angleton, about 40 miles (60 kilometers) south of
Houston, after the videotape was showed.
</P>
<P>
Clark said the FBI, which is investigating whether prisoners'
civil rights were violated, would submit findings to the U.S.
attorney's office in Houston and the Department of Justice.
</P>
<P>
Charles Wagner, chief deputy at the jail, denied that there was
brutality in the jail.
</P>
<P>
He said he told the guards: "Well, you have a training film
that shows what not to do."
</P>
<P>
"There's not any real brutality," he told The Brazosport Facts
newspaper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
