<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Grants Soft Loan to Cameroun </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) today approved a three-year loan of about 219 million
U.S. dollars to Cameroun to support its economic program.
</P>
<P>
The loan would help fund a 1997-2000 program designed to
achieve a real annual GDP growth of at least 5 percent, an average
annual inflation of 2 percent, and a 2 percent ratio of current
account deficit against GDP.
</P>
<P>
The loan carries a yearly interest rate of 0.5 percent and is
repayable over 10 years, with a 5.5-year grace period.
</P>
<P>
The fund, under the Enhanced Structural Adjustment Facility
(ESAF), would contribute to the country's drive to obtain the
medium-term goal of putting the economy on a sustainable growth
path.
</P>
<P>
Cameroun joined the IMF in July 1963. The EASF is a
concessional IMF facility to assist member countries in their
economic reforms to achieve balance of payment and boost growth.
</P>
</TEXT>
