<HEADLINE> hke082112 - Myanmar Minister Calls for Boosting Marine Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar Commerce Minister Tun Kyi
has called for boosting marine production and increasing the
number of fishing vessels which carry daily a large amount of fish
and prawns to Yangon.
</P>
<P>
Meeting with officials of the sector here Wednesday, Commerce
Minister Tun Kyi said the aim of the move is to increase supply
for domestic consumption and boost export for earning substantial
foreign exchange, The New Light of Myanmar reported today.
</P>
<P>
The minister also urged the marine sector to provide fishing
gear, distribute sufficient supply of prawn larvae, introduce
advanced production methods, reclaim more land for fish and prawn
breeding.
</P>
<P>
The Myanmar government has permitted local private
entrepreneurs to operate some leasable fisheries.
</P>
<P>
It has also given permission to private organizations to import
off-shore fishing vessels.
</P>
<P>
Total foreign investment in livestock breeding and fishery
sector had reached 269.54 million U.S. dollars in 17 permitted
projects by the end of July this year, according to the latest
official statistics.
</P>
<P>
Foreign companies investing in Myanmar's fishery sector have
reportedly come from Thailand, China, Japan and Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar exploited about 590,000 tons of marine products
annually in the past few years out of the maximum sustainable
yield which is estimated at about 1.05 million tons per year.
</P>
<P>
The fresh water fish and marine fish production of the country
registered an annual growth rate of 8.9 and 39.5 percent
respectively in the 1996-97 fiscal year ending March.
</P>
<P>
The total export of livestock and fishery sector in the same
fiscal year amounted to 726 million kyats (121 million U.S.
dollars according to official exchange rate) with fish and prawn
as major export items. 
</P>
