<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgaria Prepares to Switch to Professional Army </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The first experiment in recruiting
professional soldiers in Bulgaria is scheduled for October 1,
Bulgarian Defense Minister Georgi Ananiev told a news conference
today.
</P>
<P>
An order for this was issued on Monday by Bulgarian Chief of
General Staff, General Mikho Mikhov, and was given for endorsement
to the defense minister.
</P>
<P>
The experimental recruitment of 120 soldiers will prepare the
way for the second stage of reform in the Bulgarian armed forces,
a switch to a professional army due to be completed in the coming
years, said Ananiev. An updated strategy for the development of
the Bulgarian army envisaged the formation of professional-only
units, he said.
</P>
<P>
The stage-by-stage transition to a professional army was
necessitated by the population drop and the ever decreasing number
of conscripts, said the Minister.
</P>
<P>
The enlisted must meet requirements formulated in the Armed
Forces Act and requirements of the vacant military positions.
Under the law, only Bulgarian citizens under 35 years old who have
gone through general conscription and have no criminal record
qualify for enlistment. Contracts will be for three years, with a
possibility of extensions.
</P>
<P>
The Army, the Air Force and the Navy are each expected have 24
to 25 positions for volunteers. Forty-seven of the new enlisted
will serve in a newly-established Zone Headquarters that will
bring together the Sofia City, District and Regional Draft
Registration Offices.
</P>
<P>
The experiment, initially scheduled for February 1996 when the
Defense and Armed Forces Act was enforced, was delayed by money
shortages.
</P>
<P>
The professional soldiers will get a monthly salary of 127,910
leva (about 304.50 U.S. dollars) in the Army, 131,410 leva (3l3
dollars) in the Air Force and 193,430 leva (460 dollars) in the
Navy. Estimates by the General Staff show that a conscript costs
slightly more than that in upkeep.
</P>
<P>
Ananiev said that if the 1998 armed forces budget allocated
funds for recruiting professional soldiers, the General Staff
would be ready to utilize them immediately.
</P>
<P>
There are plans for reinstating a marine battalion and
positions in it would be available for the enlisted. Professional
soldiers would also be appointed to a Bulgarian-Turkish battalion
of blue helmets that was under preparation, Ananiev added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
