<HEADLINE> Thai Auto Industry to Cut 32,000 Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 21 (Xinhua) -- At least 32,000 employees of
local car and parts industry are expected to be laid off by the
end of the year, according to the Automotive and Parts Association
of Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Most Japanese manufacturers, with the exception of Honda, have
decided to cut productivity by 50 percent to reduce costs, Ninnart
Chaiteerapinyo, president of the association was quoted by today's
local press as saying.
</P>
<P>
The industry employs about a quarter of a million people in
production, marketing, distribution and support.
</P>
<P>
In the last two months, car firms and dealers have laid off
some 2,500 employees.
</P>
<P>
Car sales have dropped dramatically in the wake of the baht
depreciation on July 2. It is expected that total car sales
(including pick-up) will shrink by 40 percent to 360,000 units
this year from 589,000 units last year.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of the year, 248,185 cars were sold
domestically and 14,000 exported. Domestic sales have declined
14.5 percent against the same period in 1996.  
