<HEADLINE> Nicaraguan Toxic Residues to be Incinerated in Finland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- About 200 tons of DDT and
heptachlorine toxic residues will be shipped Thursday to the
Ekokem company, Finland, for incineration, sources from the
Nicaraguan Ministry of Environment and Natural Resources said
today.
</P>
<P>
Nicaragua signed recently a contract with the company on the
shipment and destruction of the chemical wastes.
</P>
<P>
DDT and heptachlorine, banned worldwide for decades, were used
in Nicaragua until 1990 to kill malaria, yellow fever and dengue
mosquitos and for plague control on cotton fields.
</P>
<P>
Those toxic wastes can cause mortal diseases such as cancer and
damage fetus in pregnant women and fertility in men.
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, the Latin American countries do not have suitable
equipment to destroy them and thus have to do it in Finland at the
cost of the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Ekokem company has treated toxic residues in Riihimaki,
Finland, since 1984, and is currently handling around 80,000 tons
yearly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
