<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Exports from State-Owned Companies Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Exports from China's State-owned
enterprises (SOEs) posted a substantial rise in the first half of
this year while imports were down.
</P>
<P>
Customs statistics indicate that exports by SOEs during that
period soared 25.2 percent from a year ago to 45.67 billion US
dollars while imports stood at 27.11 billion, down 5.6 percent on
a year-on-year basis.
</P>
<P>
The solid increases in exports by SOEs since the beginning of
this year are partly because SOEs have adapted themselves to state
policy adjustments, the "China Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
As the state reduced its rebate rates, exports by SOEs plunged
during the first half of 1996. They started to bottom out later
last year when the state sped up its work to pay back the rebates
and most SOEs gradually adapted themselves to the new policy by
deepening their internal reforms, it said.
</P>
<P>
The negative growth in imports by SOEs mainly stemmed from
sluggish domestic demand, unsatisfactory economic returns of some
SOEs and their shortage of working capital.
</P>
<P>
Customs statistics also suggested that general trade retained
its dominant position in SOEs foreign trade in the period. General
exports jumped 31.5 percent to 29.57 billion US dollars and
imports declined 14.1 percent to 13.3 billion dollars, making up
64.7 percent and 49.1 percent of SOEs' exports and imports in the
period, respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
