<DOCNO> XIE19970821.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Officials Discuss Bosnian Serb Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- International officials today
held talks on the future of Bosnia, especially the Serb crisis, in
the Russian embassy in Vienna, the Austria Presse Agentur (APA)
news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
All participants believed that the situation in Bosnia's Serb
Republic is "grave", according to the U.S. embassy in Vienna.
</P>
<P>
The international community should fully support the force in
the Serb Republic that stands for the implementation of the Dayton
peace accords, which ended the three-and-a-half year civil war in
Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Top international official in Bosnia, Carlos Westendorp,
representatives of the Contact Group and U.S. special envoy to
Bosnia, Robert Gelbard, attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Contact Group, composed of representatives from the United
States, Russia, Britain, France and Germany, monitors the
implementation of the Dayton accords.
</P>
<P>
The talks will continue Thursday within the Organization for
Security and Cooperation in Europe, APA said.
</P>
<P>
A crisis among the Bosnian Serb leadership began in early July.
</P>
<P>
Serb President Biljana Plavsic dissolved the parliament on July
3, but the decision was strongly opposed by parliament and the
Serb government believed to be actually controlled by former
president Radovan Karadzic.
</P>
<P>
The Constitutional Court ruled last week that Plavsic's
decision was unconstitutional and invalid. Plavsic rejected the
verdict of the court.
</P>
<P>
Among the wrangling of the Serb leadership, western countries
led by the United States voiced support for Plavsic and are trying
to force Karadzic out of the political arena and bring him to
trials before the International Criminal Tribunal for former
Yugoslavia in The Hague.
</P>
<P>
Karadzic, who led Serbs in the Bosnian war, has been indicted
by the tribunal.
</P>
<P>
In the latest development, British and Czech troops of the
NATO-led multinational Stabilization Force (SFOR) today surrounded
four police stations and one police academy in Banja Luka, a
northern Bosnian town, to help Plavsic boost her authority in the
town.
</P>
<P>
Police chiefs loyal to Karadzic were removed from their posts
and truckloads of weapons were found, SFOR said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
