<HEADLINE> Weekly World Oil Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The following are weekly
news briefs on oil production and trade from all over the world:
</P>
<P>
QUITO -- Ecuador's state-owned Petroecuador company increased
its oil price for exportation by 0.1 U.S. dollar on August 1.
</P>
<P>
Ecuador's oil reached an average of 15.3 dollars per
barrel. The price hike affected exports to U.S., the Caribbean,
Peru, Argentina, Brazil and Chile.
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- Iraq resumed its oil exports on August 13, and expects
to sell 30 million barrels by the end of the month at one billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- State-run "Petroleos Mexicanos" (Pemex) has
provided the Dominican Republic with 45,000 barrels of raw oil and
other petroleum products in the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
NEW YORK -- The United Nations has ratified 16 of 22 oil
contracts included in the "oil-for-food" program, which would
permit Iraq to export a total of 83.5 million barrels of raw oil.
</P>
<P>
Four of the contracts were signed with Russian companies for
20.8 million barrels.
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- French oil company Elf Aquitaine has discovered an oil
field in the maritime zone of Angola, about 200 kilometers off the
capital Luanda.
</P>
<P>
The oil field is located 1,360 meters deep in the ocean. Trial
production performed on two spots of the field showed a
prospective production of 16,000 barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
MONTREAL -- Talisman Energy Inc. discovered a natural gas field
200 kilometers west of Edmonton, Alberta, Canada. A new well of
the field, located 4,461 meters deep in the ocean, produced 52.8
million cubic feet a day in pre-exploitation tests, 13 times of
common pre-exploitation tests, said experts with Talisman.
</P>
<P>
The well is expected to begin operation in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
