<HEADLINE> U.S. High School Students Support Death Penalty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 20 (Xinhua) -- A survey shows that some of the
brightest high school students in the United States support death
penalty on criminals as a way to check growing domestic terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The finding is part of a recent opinion poll conducted among a
group of top high school students in 46 states, the activity's
sponsor Panasonic Consumer Electronics Company said today in
Secaucus, New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey, 65 percent of the respondents said
that the death penalty on convicts like Timothy Mcveigh who was
found guilty for the Oklahoma City bombing should be imposed.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 62 percent of the people in the poll saw the
incidence of domestic terrorism on the rise.
</P>
<P>
Regarding advertising, three fourths of the respondents felt
that flashy ads would influence minors by encouraging them to buy
and smoke cigarettes, it said.
</P>
<P>
Advertisements that promote other questionable behavior to
teenagers, such as drinking, should be banned, half of the people
surveyed said.
</P>
<P>
"Today's teens have very definite opinions on domestic and
world affairs and are more knowledgeable of the issues than most
people think," a Panasonic official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970821.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Trade Deficit Declines in First Half </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's trade deficit
declined by 27.3 percent to 173.75 billion baht (6.8 billion U.S.
dollars) in the first half of this year as compared with the same
period of last year, according to official figures issued by the
Business Economics Department of the Thai government.
</P>
<P>
The fall in the deficit was attributed to an export rise of 3.6
percent to 724.06 billion baht (28.3 billion dollars) in the
period, and an import volume drop of 4.3 percent to 897.81 billion
baht (35.1 billion dollars), today's local press quoted Karun
Kittisataporn, director-general of the department as saying.
</P>
<P>
Karun said that improved export figures for the first half
reflected the real abilities of exporters since the baht had not
weakened until after the July 2 floating.
</P>
<P>
Karun said Thailand had been able to increase exports to
several key markets in the first half. Exports to the United
States were up 10.1 percent, to Malaysia up 42.9 percent, to Hong
Kong up 7.4 percent, and to China up 4.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
But, exports to Japan were down 2.6 percent, to Singapore down
2.9 percent, to the Netherlands down 8.7 percent, to Britain down
5.7 percent, and to Germany down 6.3 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
