<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Central Bank Stops Lending to Boost Peso </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Central Bank has
already suspended its overnight lending facility to banks
indefinitely as part of its bid to support the
speculation-battered local currency peso, the local press reports
said today.
</P>
<P>
The reports quoted Central Bank Treasury Director Eileen
Bautista as saying the closure of the bank's lending window
starting Wednesday has effectively reduced the ability of the
banks to "play with the foreign exchange rate."
</P>
<P>
"The unavailability of the peso means less play on the dollar,"
she explained. "Banks will be cautious to take dollars since they
will have to give up their local currencies."
</P>
<P>
Banks were caught off-guard by the Central Bank's decision to
close its lending window, a crucial source of overnight funds for
banks covering reserve deficiencies, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
The move was interpreted by some economic observers as a
prelude to increase the liquidity reserve requirement which had
already been hiked from a mere 2 percent to 5 percent on August
14.
</P>
<P>
By refusing to lend to banks, the Central Bank seeks to prevent
the infusion of additional peso liquidity into the system. Lending
to banks, observers say, is tantamount to releasing fresh money
supply into the system.
</P>
<P>
At the domestic currency market, the peso tumbled to 30.24
pesos to one dollar in intra-day trading Monday, the lowest since
its de facto devaluation starting July 11. The peso-dollar rate
appreciated slightly to an average of 30.03 pesos to one dollar
Wednesday. There was no trading Tuesday because of heavy rains.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank is reportedly standing firm on its decision to
keep itself from the currency market and let the foreign exchange
rate be determined by market forces.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
