<HEADLINE> Portuguese Water Mill Built by Romans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LISBON, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Portuguese and French
archaeologists have determined that an ancient water mill,
unearthed in 1938 in Conimbriga, central Portugal, was built
during the Roman Empire (27 B.C. -- 476 A.D.).
</P>
<P>
The local press quoted French archaeologists as saying the mill
was the only Roman relic excavated on the Iberian Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
Archaeologists said the Roman water mill was constructed
scientifically and was of good craftsmanship. 
</P>
