<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, August 21 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA -- An earthquake registering 5.8 on the Richter Scale
Wednesday rumbled Medan, the capital of Indonesia's north Sumatra
province, causing panic among residents.
</P>
<P>
The quake, which hit the area at 2:15 p.m. local time, did not
claim lives or cause any significant damage of property, Antara
news agency reported today. (Indonesia-Quake)
</P>
<P>
ATHENS -- Nine days after his disappearance, Larry Gonzales, a
U.S. airman stationed at the Souda base on the Greek island of
Crete, was found Wednesday by police in Gytheio, a seaside town in
Greece's Pelonnese peninsula.
</P>
<P>
Police said that 30-year-old Gonzales was found in a rented
room in Gytheio, holidaying with a British woman friend.
(Greece-US Airman)
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- All three major stock markets in Europe continued to
recover from recent market jitters and closed higher Wednesday,
inspired by Wall Street's resilience and the strength of the
dollar.
</P>
<P>
On the London market, British shares extended Tuesday's rebound
and finished the day with solid gains, after Wall Street built on
its overnight rally. (Europe-Stocks-Recovery)
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan strongly
urged all parties involved in Cambodia to end hostilities and
desist from all actions that would cause a further deterioration
of the situation, a UN spokesman said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Brandt Juan Carlos, associate spokesman for the
secretary-general, said that Annan viewed with deep concern the
recent outbreak of fighting in Cambodia. (UN-Cambodia)
</P>
<P>
YAOUNDE -- Heavy fighting continued in Brazzaville, capital of
Congo, between forces loyal to Congolese President Pascal Lissouba
and the militia of former president Sassou Nguesso, Radio Cameroun
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Reports from the United Nations Refugeer agency suggested
Sassou's militia captured Ouesso, the largest northern city in
Congo, and now controls the northern part of the country.
</P>
<P>
According to Radio Cameroun, 4,000 Congolese crossed the River
Congo Tuesday into neighboring Kinshasa of the Democratic Republic
of Congo. (Cameroun-heavy fighting)
