<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetan Buddhist Monasteries in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The Tibet Autonomous Region is
home to some 1,700 of China's over 3,000 Tibetan Buddhist
monasteries.
</P>
<P>
The over 130,000 monks and nuns, including 34,000 in Tibet, and
some 1,800 Living Buddhas have met the needs of Tibetan believers,
according to Cao Ziqiang, vice-president of the Advanced
Buddhism College of Tibetan Language Family.
</P>
<P>
The number of monasteries fell sharply during the chaotic
Cultural Revolution (1966-1976), a period in which respect for a
person's right to religion was nonexistent in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
However, extensive government support since the 1980s has led
to the restoration, rebuilding and reopening of large numbers of
temples. The development of Tibetan Buddhism has entered a golden
historical stage, said Cao.
</P>
<P>
He noted that central and local departments have sponsored and
established Tibetan Buddhism education in order to ensure the
continued prosperity of the religion. The relatively large-scale
education system makes used of both old and new approaches.
</P>
<P>
The traditional monastic system was introduced 1,200 years ago
and was the primary form of Tibetan Buddhist education prior to
the mid-20th century. According to Cao, this particular form of
education continues to flourish with various monasteries offering
over 600 sutra studies classes to over 10,000 student monks.
</P>
<P>
A modern education system has also formed around the Advanced
Buddhism College of the Tibetan Language Family. The college is
responsible for training senior teachers, researchers, monastic
management personnel and international Buddhist activists.
</P>
<P>
Cao added that older academic studies areas, such as
calendaring and Sabdavidya, or the science of words and their
meanings, are being appropriately protected in the face of
challenges arising during the modern era.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
