<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Firms Successful in Share Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 21 (Xinhua) -- China's state-owned enterprises
have made substantial headway in raising funds by issuing shares
overseas, according to the Shanghai's Securities News.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that by the end of July, 96 Chinese
state-owned enterprises had issued B-shares, which are
issued through the two stock exchanges in Shanghai and Shenzhen
but reserved to overseas investors only. The enterprises have so
far raised funds valued at more than three billion US dollars
through such share issues.
</P>
<P>
Another 34 enterprises have issued H-shares in Hong Kong,
pooling 56.4 billion Hong Kong dollars. The firms' combined
capitalization has reached 78.6 billion Hong Kong dollars, about
1.8 percent of the total capitalization of the Hong Kong stock
market.
</P>
<P>
To date, seven Chinese companies have issued N-shares,
referring to those issued in New York, and one Chinese company has
issued shares in Singapore, known as S-shares.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said that 54 Hong Kong-based enterprises from
inland areas have issued red chip shares in Hong Kong, raising
funds totaling 94.6 billion Hong Kong dollars. Their market
capitalization stands at 580.6 billion Hong Kong dollars, about 13
percent of the total capitalization of the Hong Kong stock
market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
