<HEADLINE> Cuba, Spain to Set up Joint Venture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Cuba and Spain will establish a
joint sugar refinery, local reports said today.
</P>
<P>
A high-tech refinery, to be launched by the Cuban government
and Spain's company Alficsa in Cuba's central province of
Cienfuegos, aims to replace Cuba's traditional raw sugar export
with more value-added product -- alcohol extracted from cane.
</P>
<P>
This is to generate more foreign currency for the country,
Cuban Vice Minister for sugar industry Francisco Rodriguez was
quoted as explaining.
</P>
<P>
Antonio Sevilla, an Alficsa official, said, his company is
confident of the capability and knowledge of experts in the sugar
sector, an important part in Cuba's economy, that also turns out
cattle fodder, paper, beverages, medicines, and chemical
substances for plastics and synthetic tissues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970821.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Irregular Businesses Increase in Costa Rica </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Irregular businesses have
increased sharply in Costa Rica since 1990, the Economy Ministry
and the Chamber of Industry said.
</P>
<P>
Irregular firms -- which are those that do not fulfill legal
requirements to operate -- rose from 4,223 in 1990 to 6,329 in
1996, a 50 percent increase, the Economy Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
In Contrast, regular companies increased slightly, from 4,463
to 4,835 in the same period, an eight percent rise.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 85 percent of newly-created companies since 1990 have
been irregular businesses, a result thought to have been brought
about by the country's economic crisis, and the numerous
requirements demanded when establishing a company.
</P>
<P>
The economy in Costa Rica has shrunk in the past two years, but
a slow growth is expected in 1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
The irregular economy has been fueled by mass layoffs because
of recent economic reform. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970821.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Beats Wales 6-4 in World Cup Qualifier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISTANBUL, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Hakan Sukur scored four goals
to help Turkey beat Wales 6-4 in a World Cup European Zone group
seven qualifier here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Wales, playing only for their pride against a Turkish team who
needed a win to maintain an outside chance of qualifying, were 2-0
down after seven minutes but stayed calm.
</P>
<P>
They came back with goals in the 18th from Nathan Blake and
22nd from Robbie Savage and then took the lead from the home side
in the 34th when Ryan Giggs sent a beautifully weighted cross into
the box for Dean Saunders to score.
</P>
<P>
Sukur, who had opened the scoring in the fifth minute,
equalised just before half-time, slotting past Ceri Hughes
outstretched foot for 3-3.
</P>
<P>
Wales again took the lead in the 52nd minute through Andy
Melville but Sukur grabbed two more in the 72nd and 83rd minutes
to put the result beyond doubt.
</P>
<P>
Turkey have 10 points from six games, five points behind the
group leaders Netherlands and Belgium. 
</P>
</TEXT>
