<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Australian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Australian newspapers published today:
</P>
<P>
The Australian
</P>
<P>
-- Inherited breast cancer is much rarer than previously
thought, with Australian research suggesting only five percent of
cancers in women under 40 are caused by one of the known breast
cancer genes, rather than the 30 percent scientists quoted
previously.
</P>
<P>
-- Economic cycles in East Asian countries appear to be
replacing those in the United States as the driving forces behind
short-term fluctuations in Australia's growth, leaving local
exporters vulnerable to the vagaries of the tiger economies.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Morning Herald
</P>
<P>
-- Aborigines in Australia signed an agreement yesterday which
for the first time guarantees a company the right to explore and
mine the entire northeast Kimberley region in Western Australia.
The deal gives a diamond miner the right to explore the vast area
and to develop open-cut mines without further talks with
traditional owners or reference to native titles laws if the land
is claimed by aborigines.
</P>
<P>
The Age
</P>
<P>
-- Australian troops may be deployed in Bougainville in
neighboring Papua New Guinea as part of a United Nations-sponsored
peace mission to the war-ravaged Pacific island, according to a
secret contingency plan made by the Australian Defense Force.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Financial Review
</P>
<P>
-- The Australian government has revamped its information
technology outsourcing policy, now ranking industry development
commitments equally with price in awarding future contracts in the
country's 5.18 billion US dollar information technology market.
</P>
</TEXT>
