<DOCNO> XIE19970821.0287 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece Dismisses Turkish Official's Statements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Greece today dismissed the
statements made by Turkey's Deputy Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit,
saying that such statements ran completely contrary to the letter
and spirit of the joint communique signed between the two
countries in Madrid.
</P>
<P>
In statements to a Turkish daily newspaper Tuesday, Ecevit
expressed displeasure with the European Union (EU) for supposedly
"excluding" Ankara and accepting Cyprus for membership. He also
rejected as "ridiculous" the possibility of Turkey having recourse
to the international court at the Hague over its territorial
claims on the Greek islets of Imia.
</P>
<P>
Greek government spokesman Dimitris Reppas today criticized
Ecevit's statements as "lacking seriousness and responsibility,"
warning that Ankara's such policy left no room for an improvement
of Greek-Turkish ties, nor for progress in the neighboring
country's relations with the EU.
</P>
<P>
As for the Cyprus problem, Reppas said that if the statements
reflected official Turkish policy, then they made any continuation
of talks to resolve the Cyprus problem "meaningless."
</P>
<P>
The European Commission has planned to start accession talks
with Cyprus early next year, triggering strong opposition from
both Turkish Cypriots and Turkey, which itself has made efforts
for years for full EU membership.
</P>
<P>
Turkey today called on the EU to reconsider its accession talks
with the Cypriot government, stressing that it has an important
bearing on the settlement of the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus issue has remained unresolved since 1974 when the
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern part of the
island in the wake of an abortive coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970821.0288 </DOCNO>
